# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: artistic-billiards-world-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The city is one of Mexico's oldest beach resorts, coming into prominence in the 1940s through the 1960s as a getaway for Hollywood stars and millionaires.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco was once a popular tourist resort, but due to a massive upsurge in gang violence and homicide numbers since 2014, Acapulco no longer attracts many foreign tourists, and most now only come from within Mexico itself.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It is both the ninth deadliest city in Mexico and the tenth-deadliest city in the world as of 2022; the US government has warned its citizens not to travel there.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 2016 there were 918 murders, and the homicide rate was one of the highest in the world: 103 in every 100,000.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In September 2018, the city's entire police force was disarmed by the military, due to suspicions that it had been infiltrated by drug gangs.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The name "Acapulco, Guerrero" comes from Nahuatl language *Aca-pōl-co*, and means "where the reeds were destroyed or washed away" or "at the big reeds", which inspired the city's seal, which is an Aztec-type glyph showing two hands breaking reeds.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The "de Juárez" was added to the official name in 1885 to honor Benito Juárez, former president of Mexico (1806–1872).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The island and municipality of Capul, in the Philippines, derives its name from Acapulco, Guerrero.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco, Guerrero was the eastern end of the trans-Pacific sailing route from Acapulco to Manila, in what was then a Spanish colony.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] By the 8th century, around the Acapulco Bay area, there was a small culture which would first be dominated by the Olmecs, then by a number of others during the pre-Hispanic period before it ended in the 1520s.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] At Acapulco Bay itself, there were two Olmec sites, one by Playa Larga and the other on a hill known as *El Guitarrón*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Olmec influence caused the small spread-out villages here to coalesce into larger entities and build ceremonial centers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Later, Teotihuacan influence came to the area via Cuernavaca and Chilpancingo.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Then Mayan influence arrived from the Isthmus of Tehuantepec and through what is now Oaxaca.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This history is known through the archaeological artifacts that have been found here, especially at *Playa Hornos, Pie de la Cuesta*, and *Tambuco*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the 11th century, new waves of migration of Nahuas, including the *Coixcas*, came through here.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] These people were the antecedents of the Aztecs.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the later 15th century, after four years of military struggle, Acapulco became part of the Aztec Empire during the reign of Ahuizotl (1486–1502).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It was annexed to a tributary province centered at Tecpan de Galeana.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] However, this was only transitory, as the Aztecs could only establish an unorganized military post at the city's outskirts.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The city was in territory under control of the *Yopis*, who continued defending it and living there until the arrival of the Spanish in the 1520s.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There are two stories about how Acapulco bay was discovered by Europeans.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The first states that two years after the Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire, Hernán Cortés sent explorers west to find gold.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The explorers had subdued this area after 1523, and Captain Saavedra Cerón was authorized by Cortés to found a settlement here.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The other states that the bay was discovered on December 13, 1526, by a small ship named the El Tepache Santiago captained by Santiago Guevara.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The first encomendero was established in 1525 at *Cacahuatepec*, which is still part of the modern Acapulco municipality.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1531, a number of Spaniards, most notably Juan Rodriguez de Villafuerte, left the Oaxaca coast and founded the village of Villafuerte where the city of Acapulco now stands.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Villafuerte was unable to subdue the local native peoples, and this eventually resulted in the Yopa Rebellion in the region of *Cuautepec*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Hernán Cortés was obligated to send Vasco Porcayo to negotiate with the indigenous people giving concessions.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The province of Acapulco became the encomendero of Rodriguez de Villafuerte who received taxes in the form of cocoa, cotton and corn.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Cortés established Acapulco as a major port by the early 1530s, with the first major road between Mexico City and the port constructed by 1531.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The wharf, named Marqués, was constructed by 1533 between Bruja Point and Diamond Point.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Soon after, the area was made an "alcadia" (major province or town).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Spanish trade with the Far East gave Acapulco a prominent place in the economy of New Spain.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1550, thirty Spanish families were sent from Mexico City to establish a permanent base of European residents.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Galleons began arriving from Asia in 1565, and the Manila-Acapulco trade route made Acapulco the second most important port in New Spain after Veracruz.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1573, the Crown granted a monopoly on trade with Manila and Acapulco became a center of communication between Europe, Asia, and the Americas.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] On January 25, 1614, a delegation led by samurai Hasekura Tsunenaga, which included over one hundred Japanese Christians as well as twenty-two samurai under the shōgun Tokugawa Ieyasu, arrived from Japan to Acapulco as part of a mission to form closer relations with Catholic Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] A fight soon broke out in which a Japanese samurai stabbed a Spanish colonial soldier in Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This was witnessed and recorded by historian Chimalpahin, who was the grandson of an Aztec nobleman.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Some of Tsunenaga's delegation would stay and marry with the locals.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The galleon trade made its yearly run from the mid-16th century until the early 19th.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The luxury items it brought to New Spain attracted the attention of English and Dutch pirates, such as Francis Drake, Henry Morgan and Thomas Cavendish, who called it "The Black Ship".
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] A Dutch fleet invaded Acapulco in 1615, destroying much of the town before being driven off.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Fort of San Diego was built the following year to protect the port and the cargo of arriving ships.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The fort was destroyed by an earthquake in 1776 and was rebuilt between 1778 and 1783.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] At the beginning of the 19th century, King Charles IV declared Acapulco a Ciudad Official and it became an essential part of the Spanish Crown.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] However, not long after, the Mexican War of Independence began.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1810, José María Morelos y Pavón attacked and burnt down the city, after he defeated royalist commander Francisco Parés at the Battle of Tres Palos.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The independence of Mexico in 1821 ended the run of the Manila Galleon.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco's importance as a port recovered during the California Gold Rush in the mid-19th-century, with ships going to and coming from Panama stopping here.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This city was besieged on April 19, 1854 by Antonio López de Santa Anna after Guerrero's leadership had rebelled by issuing the Plan de Ayutla.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] After an unsuccessful week of fighting, Santa Anna retreated.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1911, revolutionary forces took over the main plaza of Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1920, the Prince of Wales (the future King Edward VIII) visited the area.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Impressed by what he saw, he recommended the place to his compatriots in Europe, making it popular with the elite there.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Much of the original hotel and trading infrastructure was built by a businessman named Albert B.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Pullen from Corrigan, Texas, in the area now known as Old Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1933, Carlos Barnard started the first section of *Hotel El Mirador*, with 12 rooms on the cliffs of La Quebrada.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Albert Pullen built the *Las Americas Hotel*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the late 1930s, "La Fraccionadora de Acapulco, S.A." (FASA), consisting of William Pullen, Anacleto Martínez, Juan M.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Salcedo, and Wolf Schoenburg, who was especially instrumental, started tourism development in earnest.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the mid-1940s, the first commercial wharf and warehouses were built.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the early 1950s, President Miguel Alemán Valdés upgraded the port's infrastructure, installing electrical lines, drainage systems, roads and the first highway to connect the port with Mexico City.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The economy grew and foreign investment increased with it.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] During the 1950s, Acapulco became the fashionable place for millionaire Hollywood stars such as Elizabeth Taylor, Frank Sinatra, Eddie Fisher and Brigitte Bardot.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The 1963 Hollywood movie *Fun in Acapulco*, starring Elvis Presley, is set in Acapulco although the filming took place in the United States.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Former swing musician Teddy Stauffer, the so-called "Mister Acapulco", was a hotel manager ("Villa Vera", "Casablanca"), who attracted many celebrities to Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] From a population of only 4,000 or 5,000 in the 1940s, by the early 1960s, Acapulco had a population of about 50,000.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1958, the Diocese of Acapulco was created by Pope Pius XII.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] During the 1960s and 1970s, new hotel resorts were built, and accommodation and transport were made cheaper.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It was no longer necessary to be a millionaire to spend a holiday in Acapulco; the foreign and Mexican middle class could now afford to travel here.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] However, as more hotels were built in the south part of the bay, the old hotels of the 1950s lost their grandeur.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] For the 1968 Summer Olympics in neighboring Mexico City, Acapulco hosted the sailing (then yachting) events.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the 1970s, there was a significant expansion of the port.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Miss Universe 1978 pageant took place in the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1983, singer-songwriter Juan Gabriel wrote the song "Amor eterno", which pays homage to Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The song was first and most famously recorded by Rocío Dúrcal.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Additionally, Acapulco is the hometown of actress, singer, and comedian Aída Pierce, who found fame during the 1980s, 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 1993, a section of Mexican Federal Highway 95D, nicknamed *Autopista del Sol* was built, crossing the mountains between Mexico City and Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The journey takes only about three-and-a-half hours, making Acapulco a favorite weekend destination for Mexico City inhabitants.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The port continued to grow and in 1996, a new private company, API Acapulco, was created to manage operations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This consolidated operations and now Acapulco is the major port for car exports to the Pacific.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The city was devastated by Hurricane Pauline in 1997.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The storm stranded tourists and left more than 100 dead in the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Most of the victims were from the shantytowns built on steep hillsides that surround the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Other victims were swept away by the winds and waves.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The main road, Avenida Costera, became a fast-moving river of sludge three feet (0.91 m) in depth.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the 21st century, the Mexican drug war has had a negative effect on tourism in Acapulco as rival drug cartels fight each other for the Guerrero coast route that brings drugs from South America as well as soldiers that have been fighting the cartels since 2006.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] A major gun battle between 18 gunmen and soldiers took place in the summer of 2009 in the Old Acapulco seaside area, lasting hours and killing 16 of the gunmen and two soldiers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This came after the 2009 swine flu pandemic outbreak earlier in the year nearly paralyzed the Mexican economy, forcing hotels to give discounts to bring tourists back.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] However, hotel occupancy for 2009 was down five percent from the year before.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The death of Arturo Beltrán Leyva in December 2009 resulted in infighting among different groups within the Beltrán Leyva cartel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Gang violence continued to plague Acapulco through 2010 and into 2011, most notably with at least 15 dying in drug-related violence on March 13, 2010, and another 15 deaths on January 8, 2011.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Among the first incident's dead were six members of the city police and the brother of an ex-mayor.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the second incident, the headless bodies of 15 young men were found dumped near the Plaza Sendero shopping center.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] On August 20, 2011, Mexican authorities reported that five headless bodies were found in Acapulco, three of which were placed in the city's main tourist area and two of which were cut into multiple pieces.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] On February 4, 2013, six Spanish men were tied up and robbed and the six Spanish women with them were gang-raped by five masked gunmen who stormed a beach house on the outskirts of Acapulco, though after these accusations, none of the victims decided to press charges.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] On September 28, 2014, Mexican politician Braulio Zaragoza was gunned down at the *El Mirador* hotel in the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] He was the leader of the conservative opposition National Action Party (PAN) in southern Guerrero state.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Several politicians have been targeted by drug cartels operating in the area.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Investigations are under way, but no arrests have yet been made as of September 29.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The insecurity due to individuals involved with drug cartels has cost the city of Acapulco its popularity among national and international tourists.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 2018, the Mexican Armed Forces entered the city, placing it under occupation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The police department was disarmed after allegations of the latter being linked to the cartels.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] On October 25, 2023, Hurricane Otis, a Category 5 hurricane with 1-minute sustained winds of 160 mph (260 km/h), caused widespread devastation throughout the city while making landfall nearby.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Hurricane John struck Acapulco and Mexico's Pacific coast in late September 2024 as a Category 3 hurricane, delivering powerful winds and extreme rainfall that led to widespread flooding and significant damage.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco experienced nearly one meter of rainfall, resulting in submerged neighborhoods and serious disruptions.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Roads became impassable due to landslides, and extensive power outages left tens of thousands without electricity across Guerrero and Oaxaca.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Around 40,000 homes were damaged impacting over 150,000 residents.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The city, located on the Pacific coast of Mexico in the state of Guerrero, is classified as one of the state's seven regions, dividing the rest of the Guerrero coast into the Costa Grande and the Costa Chica.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Forty percent of the municipality is mountainous terrain; another forty percent is semi-flat; and the other twenty percent is flat.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Elevation varies from sea level to 1,699 metres (5,574 feet).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The highest peaks are *Potrero, San Nicolas*, and *Alto Camarón*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] One major river runs through the municipality, the *Papagayo*, along with a number of *arroyos* (streams).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There are also two small lagoons, Tres Palos and Coyuca, along with a number of thermal springs.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco features a tropical wet and dry climate (Köppen: Aw): hot with distinct wet and dry seasons, with more even temperatures between seasons than resorts farther north in Mexico, but this varies depending on altitude.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The warmest areas are next to the sea where the city is.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Pacific hurricanes and tropical storms are threats from May through November; notably, the city was struck directly by Category 5 Hurricane Otis on October 25, 2023, which caused extensive damage.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The forested area tends to lose leaves during the winter dry season, with evergreen pines in the highest elevations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Fauna consists mostly of deer, small mammals, a wide variety of both land and seabirds, and marine animals such as turtles.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Oddly enough, January, its coolest month, also features its all-time record high.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The temperature of the sea is quite stable, with lows of 82 °F (28 °C) between January – March, and a high of 86 °F (30 °C) in August.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] These sea surface temperatures are much warmer than those further north along the Pacific coast, and indeed warmer than most places further south, as sea surface temperatures begin to decline with proximity to the Southern Hemisphere's Humboldt Current.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] As the seat of a municipality, the city of Acapulco is the government authority for over 700 other communities, which together have a territory of 1,880.60 km2.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This municipality borders the municipalities of Chilpancingo, Juan R Escudero (Tierra Colorada), San Marcos, Coyuca de Benítez with the Pacific Ocean to the south.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The metropolitan area is made up of the municipalities of Acapulco de Juárez and Coyuca de Benitez.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The area has a population (as of 2005) of 786,830.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] For the names and terms of some Acapulco mayors, you can check a List of municipal presidents of Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It is considered the twenty-second most populous city in Mexico and the tenth most populous metropolitan area in Mexico.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It is also the city with the highest concentration of population of the homonymous municipality, representing 85.25 percent of the 789,971 inhabitants.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the 2020 census of 658,609 people where counted in the locality and 779,566 in the municipality of Acapulco, a small drop from the last census.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The metropolitan area of Acapulco is made up of six towns in the municipality of Acapulco de Juárez and four in the municipality of Coyuca de Benítez.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Tourism is the main economic activity of the municipality and most of this is centered on Acapulco Bay.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] About seventy-three percent of the municipality's population is involved in commerce, most of it related to tourism and the port.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Mining and manufacturing employ less than twenty percent and only about five percent is dedicated to agriculture.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Industrial production is limited mostly to bottling, milk products, cement products, and ice and energy production.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Agricultural products include tomatoes, corn, watermelon, beans, green chili peppers, and melons.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco is one of Mexico's oldest coastal tourist destinations, reaching prominence in the 1950s as the place where Hollywood stars and millionaires vacationed on the beach in an exotic locale.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In modern times, tourists in Acapulco have been facing problems with corrupt local police who steal money by extortion and intimidate visitors with threats of jail.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The city is divided into three tourist areas.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Traditional Acapulco is the old part of the port, where hotels like Hotel Los Flamingos, owned by personalities Johnny Weissmuller and John Wayne are located, is on the northern end of the bay.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Anchored by attractions such as the beaches of Caleta and Caletilla, the cliff divers of La Quebrada, and the city square, known as *El Zocalo*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The heyday of this part of Acapulco ran from the late 1930s until the 1960s, with development continuing through the 1980s.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This older section of town now caters to a mostly middle-class, almost exclusively Mexican clientele, while the glitzier newer section caters to the Mexican upper classes, many of whom never venture into the older, traditional part of town.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco Dorado had its development between the 1950s and the 1970s, and is about 25 minutes from the Acapulco International Airport.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It is the area that presents the most tourist influx in the port, runs through much of the Acapulco bay, from Icacos, passing through Costera Miguel Aleman Avenue, which is the main one, to Papagayo Park.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Starting at the Scenic Highway in Las Brisas, it includes Puerto Marqués and Punta Diamante and extends to Barra Vieja Beach.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It is 10 minutes from the Acapulco International Airport.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In this area, all along *Boulevard de las Naciones*, almost all transportation is by car, limousine or golf cart.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco's reputation of a high-energy party town and the nightlife have long been draws of the city for tourists.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] From November to April, luxury liners stop here daily and include ships such as the MS *Queen Victoria*, the MS *Rotterdam*, *Crystal Harmony*, and all the Princess line ships.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Despite Acapulco's international fame, most of its visitors are from central Mexico, especially the affluent from Mexico City.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco is one of the embarkation ports for the Mexican cruise line Ocean Star Cruises.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] For the Christmas season of 2009, Acapulco received 470,000 visitors, most of whom are Mexican nationals, adding 785 million pesos to the economy.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Eighty percent arrive by land and eighteen percent by air.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The area has over 25,000 condominiums, most of which function as second homes for their Mexican owners.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco is still popular with Mexican celebrities and the wealthy, such as Luis Miguel and Plácido Domingo, who maintain homes there.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Over the years, a number of problems have plagued Acapulco, especially in the bay and the older sections of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The large number of wandering vendors on the beaches, who offer everything from newspapers to massages, are a recognized problem.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It is a bother to tourists who simply want to relax on the beach, but the government says it is difficult to eradicate, as there is a lot of unemployment and poverty in the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Around the city are many small shantytowns that cling to the mountainsides, populated by migrants who have come to the city looking for work.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the last decade, drug-related violence has caused massive problems for the local tourism trade.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Another problem is the garbage that has accumulated in the bay.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Although 60.65 tons have recently been extracted from the bays of Acapulco and nearby Zihuatanejo, more needs to be done.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Most of trash removal during the off seasons is done on the beaches and in the waters closest to them.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] However, the center of the bay is not touched.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The reason trash winds up in the bay is that it is common in the city to throw it in streets, rivers and the bay itself.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The most common items cleaned out of the bay are beer bottles and car tires.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco has seen some success in this area, having several beaches receiving the high "blue flag" certifications for cleanliness and water quality.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The following are typical dishes from the region: Relleno is baked pork with a variety of vegetables and fruits such as potatoes, raisins, carrots and chiles.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It is eaten with bread called *bolillo*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Pozole is a soup with a salsa base (it can be white, red or green), hominy, meat that can be either pork or chicken and it is accompanied with *antojitos* (snacks) like tostadas, tacos and tamales.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This dish is served as part of a weekly Thursday event in the city and the state, with many restaurants offering the meal with special entertainment, from bands to dancers to celebrity impersonators.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco's main attraction is its nightlife, as it has been for many decades.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Nightclubs change names and owners frequently.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] For example, Baby 'O has been open to the national and international public since 1976 and different celebrities have visited their installations such as Mexican singer Luis Miguel, Bono from U2 and Sylvester Stallone.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Another nightclub is Palladium, located in the Escénica Avenue, the location gives the nightclub a view of the Santa Lucia Bay at night.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Informal lobby or poolside cocktail bars often offer free live entertainment.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In addition, there is the beach bar zone, where younger crowds go.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] These are located along the Costera road, face the ocean and feature techno or alternative rock.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Most are concentrated between the Fiesta Americana and Continental Plaza hotels.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] These places tend to open earlier and have more informal dress.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There is a bungee jump in this area as well.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Another attraction at Acapulco is the La Quebrada Cliff Divers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The tradition started in the 1930s when young men casually competed against each other to see who could dive from the highest point into the sea below.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Eventually, locals began to ask for tips for those coming to see the men dive.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Today the divers are professionals, diving from heights of 40 metres (130 feet) into an inlet that is only 7 metres (23 ft) wide and 4 metres (13 ft) deep, after praying first at a shrine to the Virgin of Guadalupe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] On the evening before December 12, the feast day of this Virgin, freestyle cliff divers jump into the sea to honor her.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Dives range from the simple to the complicated and end with the "Ocean of Fire" when the sea is lit with gasoline, making a circle of flames which the diver aims for.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The spectacle can be seen from a public area which charges a small fee or from the Hotel Plaza Las Glorias/El Mirador from its bar or restaurant terrace.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There are a number of beaches in the Acapulco Bay and the immediate coastline.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the bay proper there are the La Angosta (in the Quebrada), Caleta, Caletilla, Dominguillo, Tlacopanocha, Hornos, Hornitos, Honda, Tamarindo, Condesa, Guitarrón, Icacos, Playuela, Playuelilla and Playa del Secreto.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the adjoining, smaller Bay of Puerto Marqués there is Pichilingue, Las Brisas, and Playa Roqueta.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Facing open ocean just northwest of the bays is Pie de la Cuesta and southeast are Playa Revolcadero, Playa Aeromar, Playa Encantada and Barra Vieja.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Two lagoons are in the area, Coyuca to the northwest of Acapulco Bay and Tres Palos to the southeast.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Both lagoons have mangroves and offer boat tours.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Tres Palos also has sea turtle nesting areas which are protected.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In addition to sunbathing, the beaches around the bay offer a number of services, such as boat rentals, boat tours, horseback riding, scuba diving and other aquatic sports.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] One popular cruise is from Caletilla Beach to Roqueta Island, which has places to snorkel, have lunch, and a lighthouse.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There is also an underwater statue of the Virgin of Guadalupe here, created in 1958 by Armando Quesado in memory of a group of divers who died here.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Many of the scuba-diving tours come to this area as well, where there are sunken ships, sea mountains, and cave rock formations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Another popular activity is deep-sea fishing.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Fish caught here have weighed between 89 and 200 pounds.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Sailfish are so plentiful that boat captains have been known to bet with a potential customer that if he does not catch anything, the trip is free.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the old part of the city, there is a traditional main square called the Zócalo, lined with shade trees, cafés and shops.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] At the north end of the square is *Nuestra Señora de la Soledad* cathedral, with blue onion-shaped domes and Byzantine towers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The building was originally constructed as a movie set, but was later adapted into a church.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco's most historic building is the Fort of San Diego, located east of the main square and originally built in 1616 to protect the city from pirate attacks.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The fort was built by a Dutch engineer and finished in 1617 then destroyed in 1776 by an earthquake.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It was rebuilt by 1783 and this is the building that can be seen today, unchanged except for renovations done to it in 2000.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Parts of the moats remain as well as the five bulwarks and the battlements.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Today the fort serves as the Museo Histórico de Acapulco (Acapulco Historical Museum), which shows the port's history from the pre-Hispanic period until independence.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] For many years tourists could ride around the city in colorful horse-drawn carriages known as *calandrias*, but the practice ended in February 2020 due to concerns about mistreatment of the animals.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The El Rollo Acapulco is a sea-life and aquatic park located on Costera Miguel Aleman.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It offers wave pools, water slides and water toboggans.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There are also dolphin shows daily and a swim with dolphins program.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Another place that is popular with children is the *Parque Papagayo*: a large family park which has a life-sized replica of a Spanish galleon, three artificial lakes, an aviary, a skating rink, rides, go-karts and more.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Dolores Olmedo House is located in the traditional downtown of Acapulco and is noted for the murals by Diego Rivera that adorn it.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Olmedo and Rivera had been friend since Olmedo was a child and Rivera spent the last two years of his life here.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] During that time, he painted nearly nonstop and created the outside walls with tile mosaics, featuring Aztec deities such as Quetzalcoatl.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The interior of the home is covered in murals.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The home is not a museum, so only the outside murals can be seen by the public.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There is a small museum called *Casa de la Máscara* (House of Masks) which is dedicated to masks, most of them from Mexico, but there are examples from many parts of the world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The collection contains about one thousand examples and is divided into seven rooms called Masks of the World, Mexico across History, The Huichols and the Jaguar, Alebrijes, Dances of Guerrero, Devils and Death, Identity and Fantasy, and Afro-Indian masks.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Botanical Garden of Acapulco is a tropical garden located on lands owned by the Universidad Loyola del Pacífico.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Most of the plants here are native to the region, and many, such as the Peltogyne mexicana or purple stick tree, are in danger of extinction.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] One cultural event that is held yearly in Acapulco is the *Festival Internacional de la Nao*, which takes place in the Fort of San Diego, located near the Zócalo in downtown of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Festival honors the remembrance of the city's interaction and trades with Oriental territories which started back in the Sixteenth Century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Nao Festival consists of cultural activities with the support of organizations and embassies from India, China, Japan, Philippines, Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The variety of events go from film projections, musical interpretations and theatre to gastronomical classes, some of the events are specifically for kids.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The annual French Festival takes place throughout Acapulco city and offers a multitude of events that cement cultural links between Mexico and France.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The main features are a fashion show and a gourmet food fair.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Cinépolis Galerías Diana and the Teatro Juan Ruíz de Alarcón present French and French literary figures who give talks on their specialised subjects.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Even some of the local nightclubs feature French DJs.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Other festivals celebrated here include Carnival, the feast of San Isidro Labrador on 15 May, and in November, a crafts and livestock fair called the Nao de China.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There are a number of golf courses in Acapulco including the Acapulco Princess and the Pierre Marqués course, the latter designed by Robert Trent Jones in 1972 for the World Cup Golf Tournament.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Mayan Palace course was designed by Pedro Guericia and an economical course called the Club de Golf Acapulco is near the convention center.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The most exclusive course is that of the Tres Vidas Golf Club, designed by Robert von Hagge.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] It is located next to the ocean and is home to flocks of ducks and other birds.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Another famous sport tournament that has been held in Acapulco since 1993 is the Mexican Open tennis tournament, an ATP 500 event that currently takes place at the Arena GNP Seguros.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Initially it was played in clay courts but it changed to hard court.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The event has gained popularity within the passing of the years, attracting some of the top tennis players in the world including Novak Djokovic, Rafael Nadal and Marin Cilic.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Acapulco also has a bullring, called the Plaza de Toros, near Caletilla Beach.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The season runs during the winter and is called the Fiesta Brava.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Before 2010, over 100,000 American teenagers and young adults traveled to resort areas and balnearios throughout Mexico during spring break each year.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The main reason students head to Mexico is the drinking age of 18 years (versus 21 for the United States), something that has been marketed by tour operators along with the sun and ocean.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This has become attractive since the 1990s, especially since more traditional spring break places such as Daytona Beach, Florida, have enacted restrictions on drinking and other behaviors.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This legislation has pushed spring break tourism to various parts of Mexico, with Acapulco as one of the top destinations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, Cancún had been favored as the spring break destination of choice.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] However, Cancún has taken some steps to control the reckless behavior associated with the event, and students have been looking for someplace new.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] This led many more to choose Acapulco, in spite of the fact that for many travelers, the flight is longer and more expensive than to Cancún.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Many were attracted by the glitzy hotels on the south side and Acapulco's famous nightlife.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 2008, 22,500 students came to Acapulco for spring break.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Hotels did not get that many in 2009, due mostly to the economic situation in the United States, and partially because of scares of drug-related violence.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In February 2009, the US State Department issued a travel alert directed at college students planning spring break trips to Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The warning—a result of violent activity springing from Mexico's drug cartel débâcle—took college campuses by storm, with some schools going so far as to warn their students about the risks of travel to Mexico over spring break.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Bill O'Reilly devoted a segment of his show, *The O'Reilly Factor*, to urge students to stay away from Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In June 2009, a number of incidents occurred between the drug cartel and the government.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] These included coordinated attacks on police headquarters and open battles in the streets, involving large-caliber weapons and grenades.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] However, no incidents of violence against travelers on spring break were reported.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Nine passenger airlines, including four international ones, fly to Acapulco International Airport.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In the city, there are many buses and taxi services one can take to get from place to place, but most of the locals choose to walk to their destinations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] However, an important mode of transportation is the government-subsidized 'Colectivo' cab system.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] These cabs cost 13 pesos per person to ride, but they are not private.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The driver will pick up more passengers as long as seats are available, and will transport them to their destination based on first-come, first-served rules.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The colectivos each travel a designated area of the city, the three main ones being Costera, Colosio, Coloso, or a mixture of the three.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Coloso cabs travel mainly to old Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Colosio cabs travel through most of the tourist area of Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Costera cabs drive up and down the coast of Acapulco, where most of the hotels for visitors are located, but which includes some of old Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Drivers have discretion over destinations; some are willing to travel to the other designated areas, especially during slow periods of the day.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The bus system is highly complex and can be rather confusing to an outsider.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] As far as transportation goes, it is the cheapest form, other than walking, in Acapulco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The most expensive buses have air conditioning, while the cheaper buses do not.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] For tourists, the Acapulco city government has established a system of yellow buses with Acapulco painted on the side of them.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] These buses are not for tourists only, but are certainly the nicest and most uniform of the bus systems.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] These buses travel the tourist section of Acapulco, driving up and down the coast.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] There are buses with specific routes and destinations, generally written on their windshields or shouted out by a barker riding in the front seat.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Perhaps the most unusual thing about the privately operated buses is the fact that they are all highly decorated and personalized, with decals and home-made interior designs that range from comic book scenes, to pornography, and even to "Hello Kitty" themes.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The bus network was simplified on 25 June 2016 with the implementation of the Acabús.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The bus rapid transit system spans 36.2 kilometres (22.5 miles), with 16 stations spread throughout the city of Acapulco along five routes.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Boarding is sped by prepayment at stations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] In 2014, the idea to nominate the Manila-Acapulco Galleon Trade Route was initiated by the Mexican ambassador to UNESCO with the Filipino ambassador to UNESCO.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] An Experts' Roundtable Meeting was held at the University of Santo Tomas (UST) on April 23, 2015, as part of the preparation of the Philippines for the possible transnational nomination of the Manila-Acapulco Galleon Trade Route to the World Heritage List.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The nomination will be made jointly with Mexico.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The following are the experts and the topics they discussed during the roundtable meeting: Dr.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Bolunia on Shipyards in the Bicol Region; Mr.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Sheldon Clyde Jago-on, Bobby Orillaneda, and Ligaya Lacsina on Underwater Archaeology; Dr.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Leovino Garcia on Maps and Cartography; Fr.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Rene Javellana, S.J. on Fortifications in the Philippines; Felice Sta.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Fernando Zialcita on Textile; and Regalado Trota Jose on Historical Dimension.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The papers presented and discussed during the roundtable meeting will be synthesized into a working document to establish the route's Outstanding Universal Value.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] The Mexican side reiterated that they will also follow suit with the preparations for the route's nomination.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/acapulco] Spain has also backed the nomination of the Manila-Acapulco Trade Route in the UNESCO World Heritage Site list and has also suggested the Archives of the Manila-Acapulco Galleons to be nominated as part of a separate UNESCO list, the UNESCO Memory of the World Register.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships** are the World Championships for aerobic gymnastics.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] American snooker has a simplified rule set compared to the international game, and is usually played on smaller tables.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] Depending upon equipment availability, the balls and *pockets* may be larger than those for standard snooker, up to the size of pool balls and pockets.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] The United States Snooker Association is not connected with the game of American snooker, being the IBSF-recognized US governing body of standard-rules snooker.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] American snooker made its first known in-print appearance in the 1925 edition of Brunswick–Balke–Collender Co.'s *Rules Governing the Royal Game of Billiards*, a rulebook given away by the company (with illustrations of their tables) as a promotional item.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] The previous edition, published in 1914, included snooker, but it was a summary of the original British version, as defined then by the Billiard Association of Great Britain and Ireland, whom the Brunswick booklet credited.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] The 1925 American version had a longer ruleset, opposite the situation today.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] Since at least as early as 1946, the Billiard Association of America (BAA), later the Billiard Congress of America (BCA), has published rules for American snooker in every edition of its near-annual rule book.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] The BCA describes the game as "a cousin of snooker as it is played broadly around the world, the regulations giving it a distinctive direction toward the configuration of many American pocket billiard games".
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] American snooker often uses 54 mm (2+1⁄8 inch) balls, but may use standard 52.5 mm (approx.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] It is typically played on a 10 by 5 ft (3.0 by 1.5 m) table (and in private homes, often on even smaller tables), as full-size regulation 12 by 6 ft (3.7 by 1.8 m) British-style tables are rare in the United States, although they are legal for American snooker.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] Most serious players obtain proper snooker cues, though novices may settle for a thicker-tipped pool cue.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] American snooker sets often come with *color balls* that are numbered with their *point* values.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] While American snooker shares many similarities to that of the modern international game of snooker, it has some differences.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] Foul shots are always awarded as a 7-point foul, as opposed to 4–7 depending on circumstances in the traditional game.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] Fouling can also occur if the cue makes contact with the table cloth, causing a 14-point foul.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] Colored balls must be pocketed cleanly, meaning that once the cue ball has struck them, they cannot make contact with any other ball before being pocketed, or it is a foul.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/american-snooker] As is more traditional with pool games, a *lag* is used in place of a coin flip at the beginning of the match, and also in the case of a *respotted* black.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was founded at the mouth of the Amstel river, which was dammed to control flooding.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Originally a small fishing village in the 12th century, Amsterdam became a major world port during the Dutch Golden Age of the 17th century, when the Netherlands was an economic powerhouse.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was the leading centre for finance and trade, as well as a hub of secular art production.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the 19th and 20th centuries, the city expanded and new neighborhoods and suburbs were built.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city has a long tradition of openness, liberalism, and tolerance.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Cycling is key to the city's modern character, and there are numerous biking paths and lanes spread throughout.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city is known for its nightlife and festival activity, with several nightclubs among the world's most famous.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Its artistic heritage, canals, and narrow canal houses with gabled façades, well-preserved legacies of the city's 17th-century Golden Age, have attracted millions of visitors annually.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange, founded in 1602, is considered the oldest "modern" securities market stock exchange in the world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] As the commercial capital of the Netherlands and one of the top financial centres in Europe, Amsterdam is considered an alpha-world city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city is the cultural capital of the Netherlands.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Many large Dutch institutions have their headquarters in the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Many of the world's largest companies are based in Amsterdam or have established their European headquarters there, such as technology companies Uber, Netflix, and Tesla.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Although Amsterdam is the official capital of the Netherlands, it is not the seat of government.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The main governmental institutions, and foreign embassies, are located in The Hague.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 2022, Amsterdam was ranked the ninth-best city to live in by the Economist Intelligence Unit and 12th on quality of living for environment and infrastructure by Mercer.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city was ranked 4th place globally as a top tech hub in 2019.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Port of Amsterdam is the fifth largest in Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The KLM hub and Amsterdam's main airport, Schiphol, is the busiest airport in the Netherlands, and third in Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Dutch capital is one of the most multicultural cities in the world, with about 180 nationalities represented.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Immigration and ethnic segregation in Amsterdam is a current issue.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's notable residents throughout its history include painters Rembrandt and Vincent van Gogh, 17th-century philosophers Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, René Descartes, and John Amos Comenius, and Holocaust victim and diarist Anne Frank.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Due to its geographical location in what used to be wet peatland, the founding of Amsterdam is later than other urban centres in the Low Countries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] However, around the area of what later became Amsterdam, farmers settled as early as three millennia ago.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] They lived along the prehistoric IJ river and upstream of its tributary Amstel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The prehistoric IJ was a shallow and quiet stream in peatland behind beach ridges.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This secluded area was able to grow into an important local settlement centre, especially in the late Bronze Age, the Iron Age and the Roman Age.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Until water issues were controlled, a permanent settlement would not have been possible, since the river mouth and the banks of the Amstel in this period in time were too wet for permanent habitation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The origins of Amsterdam are linked to the development of a dam on the Amstel River called *Amestelle*, meaning 'watery area', from *Aa(m)* 'river' + *stelle* 'site at a shoreline', 'river bank'.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In this area, land reclamation started as early as the late 10th century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amestelle was located along a side arm of the IJ.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This sidearm took its name from the eponymous land: Amstel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amestelle was inhabited by farmers, who lived more inland and more upstream, where the land was not as wet as at the banks of the downstream river mouth.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] These farmers were starting the reclamation around upstream Ouderkerk aan de Amstel, and later at the other side of the river at Amstelveen.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Van Amstel family, known in documents by this name since 1019, held the stewardship in this northwestern nook of the ecclesiastical district of the bishop of Utrecht.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The family later served also under the count of Holland.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A major turning point in the development of the Amstel River mouth was the All Saint's Flood of 1170.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In an extremely short time, the shallow river IJ turned into a wide estuary, which from then on offered the Amstel an open connection to the Zuiderzee, IJssel, and waterways further afield.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This made the water flow of the Amstel more active, so excess water could be drained better.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] With drier banks, the downstream Amstel mouth became attractive for permanent habitation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Moreover, the river had grown from an insignificant peat stream into a junction of international waterways.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A settlement was built here immediately after the landscape change of 1170.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Right from the start of its foundation it focused on traffic, production, and trade; not on farming, as opposed to how communities had lived further upstream for the past 200 years and northward for thousands of years.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The construction of a dam at the mouth of the Amstel, eponymously named Dam, is historically estimated to have occurred between 1264 and 1275.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The settlement first appeared in a document from 1275, concerning a road toll granted by the count of Holland Floris V to the residents *apud Amestelledamme* 'at the dam in the Amstel' or 'at the dam of Amstelland'.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This allowed the inhabitants of the village to travel freely through the County of Holland, paying no tolls at bridges, locks and dams.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This was a move in a years-long struggle for power in the area between the count of Holland and the Amstel family who governed the area on behalf of the bishop of Utrecht.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] By 1327, the name had developed into *Aemsterdam*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The bishop of Utrecht granted Amsterdam zone rights in either 1300 or 1306.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Mirakel van Amsterdam in 1345 rendered the city an important place of pilgrimage.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] During the heyday of the *Stille Omgang*, which became the expression of the pilgrimage after the Protestant Reformation, up to 90,000 pilgrims came to Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] From the 14th century on, Amsterdam flourished, largely from trade with the Hanseatic League.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] From the 15th century on the city established an independent trade route with the Baltic Sea in grain and timber, cutting out the Hanseatic League as middlemen.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city became the staple market of Europe for bulk cargo.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This was made possible due to innovations in the herring fishery, from which Amsterdam reaped great wealth.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Herring had demand in markets all around Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Inventions of on-board gibbing and the haringbuis in 1415, made longer voyages feasible and hence enabled Dutch fishermen to follow the herring shoals far from the coasts, giving them a monopoly in the industry.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The herring industry relied on international trade cooperation and large initial investments in ships.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This required many highly skilled and unskilled workers to cooperate, as well as the import of the necessary raw materials to turn an unfinished product into a marketable one.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This required merchants to then sell it throughout the continent and bookkeepers and accountants to divide the profit.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In short, the herring industry was setting up the foundations for what would later become the transcontinental trade system and the Dutch Golden Age, with Amsterdam at its centre, hence the saying "Amsterdam is built on Herringbones".
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Low Countries were part of the Habsburg inheritance and came under the Spanish Empire in the early sixteenth century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Dutch rebelled against Philip II of Spain, who led a defense of Catholicism during the Protestant Reformation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The main reasons for the uprising were the imposition of new taxes, the tenth penny, and the religious persecution of Protestants by the newly introduced Inquisition.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The revolt escalated into the Eighty Years' War, which ultimately led to Dutch independence.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Strongly pushed by Dutch Revolt leader William the Silent, the Dutch Republic became known for its relative religious tolerance.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Jews from the Iberian Peninsula, Protestant Huguenots from France, prosperous merchants, and printers from Flanders, and economic and religious refugees from the Spanish-controlled parts of the Low Countries found safety in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The influx of Flemish printers and the city's intellectual tolerance made Amsterdam a centre for the European free press.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] During the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced what is considered its *Golden Age*, during which it became the wealthiest city in the Western world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Ships sailed from Amsterdam to the Baltic Sea, the Caribbean, North America, and Africa, as well as present-day Indonesia, India, Sri Lanka, and Brazil, forming the basis of a worldwide trading network.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's merchants had the largest share in both the Dutch East India Company (VOC) and the Dutch West India Company.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] These companies acquired overseas possessions that later became Dutch colonies.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was Europe's most important hub for the shipment of goods and was the leading financial centre of the Western world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1602, the Amsterdam office of the Dutch East India Company became the world's first stock exchange by trading in its own shares.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Bank of Amsterdam started operations in 1609, acting as a full-service bank for Dutch merchant bankers and as a reserve bank.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] From the 17th century onwards, Amsterdam also became involved in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city was a major destination port for Dutch slave ships participating in the triangular trade, which lasted until the United Netherlands abolished the Netherlands' involvement in the trade in 1814 at the request of the British government.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's prosperity declined during the 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The wars of the Dutch Republic with England (latterly, Great Britain) and France took their toll on the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars and the Napoleonic Wars, Amsterdam's significance reached its lowest point, with Holland being absorbed into the French Empire.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] However, the later establishment of the United Kingdom of the Netherlands in 1815 marked a turning point.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The end of the 19th century is sometimes called Amsterdam's second Golden Age.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] New museums, a railway station, and the Concertgebouw were built; At the same time, the Industrial Revolution reached the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam–Rhine Canal was dug to give Amsterdam a direct connection to the Rhine, and the North Sea Canal was dug to give the port a shorter connection to the North Sea.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Both projects dramatically improved commerce with the rest of Europe and the world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1906, Joseph Conrad gave a brief description of Amsterdam as seen from the seaside, in *The Mirror of the Sea*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Shortly before the First World War, the city started to expand again, and new suburbs were built.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Even though the Netherlands remained neutral in this war, Amsterdam suffered a food shortage, and heating fuel became scarce.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The shortages sparked riots in which several people were killed.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] These riots are known as the *Aardappeloproer* (Potato Rebellion).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] People started looting stores and warehouses to get supplies, mainly food.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] On 1 January 1921, after a flood in 1916, the depleted municipalities of Durgerdam, Holysloot, Zunderdorp and Schellingwoude (all lying north of Amsterdam) were, at their own request, annexed to the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Between the wars, the city continued to expand, most notably to the west of the Jordaan district in the Frederik Hendrikbuurt and surrounding neighbourhoods.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Nazi Germany invaded the Netherlands on 10 May 1940 and took control of the country.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Some Amsterdam citizens sheltered Jews, thereby exposing themselves and their families to a high risk of being imprisoned or sent to concentration camps.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] More than 100,000 Dutch Jews were deported and murdered in Nazi concentration camps, including 56,521 victims in Auschwitz and a further number of 34,082 accounted for in Sobibor.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Around 60,000 Jewish inhabitants, including Jewish prewar refugees from Austria and Germany, were living in Amsterdam at the time of the Nazi occupation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Only those provided with a safe haven, avoiding deportation and denunciation, or the very few who returned from the camps at the end of the war, managed to survive.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] At first the German occupation authorities were very cautious, wanting to convince the city inhabitants of their sincerity.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] However, their outlook soon turned to cynicism and brutality.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A cause in the change of their behaviour was an attack by a Dutch resistance fighter against a collaborator belonging to the paramilitary Dutch fascist organisation, the NSB.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The injured man died and in response Heinrich Himmler ordered reprisals.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] 427 Amsterdam Jews were arrested on 22 February 1941 and sent to Mauthausen concentration camp.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Incensed, a broad spectrum of passive resistance was organized by the Dutch Underground.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Trade unions, among them socialist and Communist Party activists, led the protest.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Their outcry received support from white collar employees in the civil service and support from the local diocese of the Church.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Approval was also given and encouraged by the Dutch government-in-exile under Queen Wilhelmina in London.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The German authorities were taken completely by surprise by the level of resistance known as the February strike.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] 300,000 people participated in the protest against the arrests of Jews.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] However, the occupier soon responded crudely and brutally, smashing union and illegal party activity.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] With the edifice of resistance removed the SS and German police apparatus, supported by collaborators in the Dutch auxiliary police, arrested thousands of defenceless Jews in Amsterdam's Jewish Quarter.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The two main waves of arrest, culminating in deportation, occurred on 26 May 1943 and on 20 June 1943.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The most famous deportee was the young Jewish girl Anne Frank, whose safe hiding place with her family was betrayed and discovered in August, 1944.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] After a spell at the 'holding camp' in Westerbork Anna and her family were sent to Auschwitz, where her mother was murdered.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] From there she and her sister Margot were moved onto Bergen-Belsen concentration camp where they died amidst appalling and inhumane conditions in early 1945.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] At the end of the Second World War, and as a consequence of the Nazi occupation, Amsterdam was in a state of crisis.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Communication with the rest of the country broke down, and food and fuel became scarce.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Many citizens traveled to the countryside to forage.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Dogs, cats, raw sugar beets, and tulip bulbs—cooked to a pulp—were consumed to stay alive.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Many trees in Amsterdam were cut down for fuel, and wood was taken from the houses, apartments and other buildings of deported Jews.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city was finally liberated by Canadian forces on 5 May 1945, shortly before the end of the war in Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Many new suburbs, such as Osdorp, Slotervaart, Slotermeer and Geuzenveld, were built in the years after the Second World War.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] These suburbs contained many public parks and wide-open spaces, and the new buildings provided improved housing conditions with larger and brighter rooms, gardens, and balconies.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Because of the war and other events of the 20th century, almost the entire city centre had fallen into disrepair.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] As society was changing, politicians and other influential figures made plans to redesign large parts of it.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] There was an increasing demand for office buildings, and also for new roads, as the automobile became available to most people.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A metro started operating in 1977 between the new suburb of Bijlmermeer in the city's Zuidoost (southeast) exclave and the centre of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Further plans were to build a new highway above the metro to connect Amsterdam Centraal and the city centre with other parts of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The required large-scale demolitions began in Amsterdam's former Jewish neighborhood.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Smaller streets, such as the Jodenbreestraat and Weesperstraat, were widened and almost all houses and buildings were demolished.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] At the peak of the demolition, the *Nieuwmarktrellen* (Nieuwmarkt riots) broke out; the rioters expressed their fury about the demolition caused by the restructuring of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] As a result, the demolition was stopped and the highway into the city's centre was never fully built; only the metro was completed.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The new city hall was built on the almost completely demolished Waterlooplein.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Meanwhile, large private organizations, such as *Stadsherstel Amsterdam*, were founded to restore the entire city centre.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Although the success of this struggle is visible today, efforts for further restoration are still ongoing.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The entire city centre has reattained its former splendour and, as a whole, is now a protected area.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Many of its buildings have become monuments, and in July 2010 the Grachtengordel (the three concentric canals: Herengracht, Keizersgracht, and Prinsengracht) was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the 21st century, the Amsterdam city centre has attracted large numbers of tourists: between 2012 and 2015, the annual number of visitors rose from 10 to 17 million.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Real estate prices have surged, and local shops are making way for tourist-oriented ones, making the centre unaffordable for the city's inhabitants.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] These developments have evoked comparisons with Venice, a city thought to be overwhelmed by the tourist influx.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Construction of a new metro line connecting the part of the city north of the IJ to its southern part was started in 2003.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The project was controversial because its cost had exceeded its budget by a factor of three by 2008, because of fears of damage to buildings in the centre, and because construction had to be halted and restarted multiple times.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The new metro line was completed in 2018.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Since 2014, renewed focus has been given to urban regeneration and renewal, especially in areas directly bordering the city centre, such as Frederik Hendrikbuurt.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This urban renewal and expansion of the traditional centre of the city—with the construction of artificial islands of the new eastern IJburg neighbourhood—is part of the Structural Vision Amsterdam 2040 initiative.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is located in the Western Netherlands, in the province of North Holland, the capital of which is not Amsterdam, but rather Haarlem.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The river Amstel ends in the city centre and connects to a large number of canals that eventually terminate in the IJ.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's elevation is about −2 m (−6.6 ft) below sea level.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The surrounding land is flat as it is formed of large polders.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] An artificial forest, Amsterdamse Bos, is in the southwest.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is connected to the North Sea by the North Sea Canal.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is intensely urbanised, as is the Metropolitan Region Amsterdam surrounding the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Comprising 219.4 km2 (84.7 sq mi) of land, the city proper has 4,457 inhabitants per km2 and 2,275 houses per km2.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Parks and nature reserves make up 12% of Amsterdam's land area.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has more than 100 km (60 mi) of canals, most of which are navigable by boat.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city's three main canals are the Prinsengracht, the Herengracht, and the Keizersgracht.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the Middle Ages, Amsterdam was surrounded by a moat, called the Singel, which now forms the innermost ring in the city, and gives the city centre a horseshoe shape.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] It has been compared with Venice, due to its division into about 90 islands, which are linked by more than 1,200 bridges.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*) strongly influenced by its proximity to the North Sea to the west, with prevailing westerly winds.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam, as well as most of the North Holland province, lies in USDA Hardiness zone 8b.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Frosts mainly occur during spells of easterly or northeasterly winds from the inner European continent.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Even then, because Amsterdam is surrounded on three sides by large bodies of water, as well as having a significant heat-island effect, nights rarely fall below −5 °C (23 °F), while it could easily be −12 °C (10 °F) in Hilversum, 25 km (16 mi) southeast.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Summers are moderately warm with several hot and humid days with occasional rain every month.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The average daily high in August is 22.1 °C (72 °F), and 30 °C (86 °F) or higher is only measured on average on 2.5 days, placing Amsterdam in AHS Heat Zone 2.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Days with more than 1 mm (0.04 in) of precipitation are common, on average 133 days per year.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's average annual precipitation is 838 mm (33 in).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A large part of this precipitation falls as light rain or brief showers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Cloudy and damp days are common during the cooler months of October through March.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1300, Amsterdam's population was around 1,000 people.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] While many towns in Holland experienced population decline during the 15th and 16th centuries, Amsterdam's population grew, mainly due to the rise of the profitable Baltic maritime trade especially in grain after the Burgundian victory in the Dutch–Hanseatic War in 1441.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The population of Amsterdam was only modest compared to the towns and cities of Flanders and Brabant, which comprised the most urbanized area of the Low Countries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This changed when, during the Dutch Revolt, many people from the Southern Netherlands fled to the North, especially after Antwerp fell to Spanish forces in 1585.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Jews from Spain, Portugal, and Eastern Europe similarly settled in Amsterdam, as did Germans and Scandinavians.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In thirty years, Amsterdam's population more than doubled between 1585 and 1610.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] During the 1660s, Amsterdam's population reached 200,000.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city's growth levelled off and the population stabilized around 240,000 for most of the 18th century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1750, Amsterdam was the fourth largest city in Western Europe, behind London (676,000), Paris (560,000) and Naples (324,000).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This was all the more remarkable as Amsterdam was neither the capital city nor the seat of government of the Dutch Republic, which itself was a much smaller state than Great Britain, France or the Ottoman Empire.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In contrast to those other metropolises, Amsterdam was also surrounded by large towns such as Leiden (about 67,000), Rotterdam (45,000), Haarlem (38,000), and Utrecht (30,000).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city's population declined in the early 19th century, dipping under 200,000 in 1820.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] By the second half of the 19th century, industrialization spurred renewed growth.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's population hit an all-time high of 872,000 in 1959, before declining in the following decades due to government-sponsored suburbanisation to so-called *groeikernen* (growth centres) such as Purmerend and Almere.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Between 1970 and 1980, Amsterdam experienced a sharp population decline, peaking at a net loss of 25,000 people in 1973.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] By 1985 the city had only 675,570 residents.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This was soon followed by reurbanization and gentrification, leading to renewed population growth in the 2010s.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Also in the 2010s, much of Amsterdam's population growth was due to immigration to the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the 16th and 17th centuries, non-Dutch immigrants to Amsterdam were mostly Protestant Huguenots and Flemings, Sephardic Jews, and Westphalians.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Huguenots came after the Edict of Fontainebleau in 1685, while the Flemish Protestants came during the Eighty Years' War against Catholic Spain.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Westphalians came to Amsterdam mostly for economic reasons; their influx continued through the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Before the Second World War, 10% of the city population was Jewish.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Just twenty percent of them survived the Holocaust.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam experienced an influx of religions and cultures after the Second World War.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] With 180 different nationalities, Amsterdam is home to one of the widest varieties of nationalities of any city in the world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The proportion of the population of immigrant origin in the city proper is about 50% and 88% of the population are Dutch citizens.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The first mass immigration in the 20th century was by people from Indonesia, who came to Amsterdam after the independence of the Dutch East Indies in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the 1960s guest workers from Turkey, Morocco, Italy, and Spain immigrated to Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] After the independence of Suriname in 1975, a large wave of Surinamese settled in Amsterdam, mostly in the Bijlmer area.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Other immigrants, including refugees asylum seekers and undocumented immigrants, came from Europe, the Americas, Asia, and Africa.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, many 'old' Amsterdammers moved to 'new' cities like Almere and Purmerend, prompted by the third Land-use planning bill of the Dutch Government.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This bill promoted suburbanization and arranged for new developments in so-called "groeikernen", literally *cores of growth*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Young professionals and artists moved into neighborhoods De Pijp and the Jordaan abandoned by these Amsterdammers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The non-Western immigrants settled mostly in the social housing projects in Amsterdam-West and the Bijlmer.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 2006, people of non-Western origin made up approximately one-fifth of the population of Amsterdam, and more than 30% of the city's children.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A slight majority of the residents of Amsterdam have at least one parent who was born outside the country.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] However, a much larger majority has at least one parent who was born inside the country (intercultural marriages are common in the city).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Only a third of inhabitants under 15 are *autochthons (*person with two parents of Dutch origin).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 2023, *autochthons* were a minority in 40% of Amsterdam's neighborhoods.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Segregation along ethnic lines is visible, with people of non-Western origin, considered a separate group by Statistics Netherlands, concentrating in specific neighborhoods especially in Nieuw-West, Zeeburg, Bijlmer and in certain areas of Amsterdam-Noord.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 2000, Christians formed the largest religious group in the city (28% of the population).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The next largest religion was Islam (8%), most of whose followers were Sunni.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] By 2015, this remained largely unchanged, with a slight decrease in the Muslim population to 7.1%.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has been one of the municipalities in the Netherlands that provided immigrants with extensive and free Dutch-language courses, which have benefited many immigrants.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1578, the largely Catholic city of Amsterdam joined the revolt against Spanish rule, late in comparison to other major northern Dutch cities.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Catholic priests were driven out of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Following the Dutch takeover, all churches were converted to Protestant worship.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Calvinism was declared the main religion.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] It was forbidden to openly profess Roman Catholicism and the Catholic hierarchy was prohibited until the mid-19th century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This led to the establishment of clandestine churches, covert religious buildings hidden in pre-existing buildings.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Catholics, some Jews, and dissenting Protestants worshipped in such buildings.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A large influx of foreigners of many religions came to 17th-century Amsterdam, in particular Sephardic Jews from Spain and Portugal, Huguenots from France, Lutherans, Mennonites, as well as Protestants from across the Netherlands.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This led to the establishment of many non-Dutch-speaking churches.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1603, the Jewish received permission to practice their religion in the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1639, the first synagogue was consecrated.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Jews came to call the town "Jerusalem of the West".
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] As they became established in the city, other Christian denominations used converted Catholic chapels to conduct their own services.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The oldest English-language church congregation in the world outside the United Kingdom is found at the Begijnhof.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Regular services there are still offered in English under the auspices of the Church of Scotland.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Being Calvinists, the Huguenots soon integrated into the Dutch Reformed Church, though often retaining their own congregations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Some, commonly referred to by the moniker 'Walloon', are recognizable today as they offer occasional services in French.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the second half of the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced an influx of Ashkenazim, Jews from Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Jews often fled the pogroms in those areas.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The first Ashkenazis who arrived in Amsterdam were refugees from the Khmelnytsky uprising occurring in Ukraine and the Thirty Years' War, which devastated much of Central Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] They not only founded their own synagogues but had a strong influence on the 'Amsterdam dialect' adding a large Yiddish local vocabulary.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Despite an absence of an official Jewish ghetto, most Jews preferred to live in the eastern part, which used to be the centre of medieval Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The main street of this Jewish neighbourhood was Jodenbreestraat.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhood comprised the Waterlooplein and the Nieuwmarkt.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Buildings in this neighbourhood fell into disrepair after the Second World War a large section of the neighbourhood was demolished during the construction of the metro system.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This led to riots, and as a result, the original plans for large-scale reconstruction were abandoned by the government.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhood was rebuilt with smaller-scale residence buildings based on its original layout.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Catholic churches in Amsterdam have been constructed since the restoration of the episcopal hierarchy in 1853.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] One of the principal architects behind the city's Catholic churches, Cuypers, was also responsible for the Amsterdam Centraal station and the Rijksmuseum.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1924, the Catholic Church hosted the International Eucharistic Congress in Amsterdam; numerous Catholic prelates visited the city, where festivities were held in churches and stadiums.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Catholic processions on the public streets, however, were still forbidden under law at the time.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Only in the 20th century was Amsterdam's relation to Catholicism normalised, but despite its far larger population size, the episcopal see of the city was placed in the provincial town of Haarlem.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Historically, Amsterdam has been predominantly Christian.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In 1900 about 70% of the city's population was Christian; the largest religious denomination was the Dutch Reformed Church, adhered to by about 45% of residents, while members of the Catholic Church formed 25%.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In recent times, the city's religious demography has diversified due to immigration from former colonies.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Hinduism has been introduced by immigrants from Suriname and several distinct branches of Islam have been brought from various parts of the world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Islam is now the largest non-Christian religion in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The large community of Ghanaian immigrants has established African churches, often in parking garages in the Bijlmer area.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam fans out south from the Amsterdam Centraal station and Damrak, the main street off the station.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The oldest area of the town is known as De Wallen (English: "The Quays").
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] It lies to the east of Damrak and contains the city's famous red-light district.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] To the south of De Wallen is the old Jewish quarter of Waterlooplein.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The medieval and colonial age canals of Amsterdam, known as *grachten*, embraces the heart of the city where homes have interesting gables.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Beyond the Grachtengordel are the former working-class areas of Jordaan and de Pijp.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Museumplein with the city's major museums, the Vondelpark, a 19th-century park named after the Dutch writer Joost van den Vondel, as well as the Plantage neighbourhood, with the zoo, are also located outside the Grachtengordel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Several parts of the city and the surrounding urban area are polders.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This can be recognised by the suffix *-meer* which means *lake*, as in Aalsmeer, Bijlmermeer, Haarlemmermeer and Watergraafsmeer.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam canal system is the result of conscious city planning.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the early 17th century, when immigration was at a peak, a comprehensive plan was developed that was based on four concentric half-circles of canals with their ends emerging at the IJ bay.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The fourth and outermost canal is the Singelgracht, which is often not mentioned on maps because it is a collective name for all canals in the outer ring.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Singelgracht should not be confused with the oldest and innermost canal, the Singel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The canals served for defense, water management and transport.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The defenses took the form of a moat and earthen dikes, with gates at transit points, but otherwise no masonry superstructures.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The original plans have been lost, so historians, such as Ed Taverne, need to speculate on the original intentions: it is thought that the considerations of the layout were purely practical and defensive rather than ornamental.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Construction started in 1613 and proceeded from west to east, across the breadth of the layout, like a gigantic windshield wiper as the historian Geert Mak calls it – and not from the centre outwards, as a popular myth has it.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The canal construction in the southern sector was completed by 1656.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Subsequently, the construction of residential buildings proceeded slowly.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The eastern part of the concentric canal plan, covering the area between the Amstel River and the IJ Bay, has never been implemented.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the following centuries, the land was used for parks, senior citizens' homes, theatres, other public facilities, and waterways without much planning.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Over the years, several canals have been filled in, becoming streets or squares, such as the Nieuwezijds Voorburgwal and the Spui.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] After the development of Amsterdam's canals in the 17th century, the city did not grow beyond its borders for two centuries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] During the 19th century, Samuel Sarphati devised a plan based on the grandeur of Paris and London at that time.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The plan envisaged the construction of new houses, public buildings, and streets just outside the Grachtengordel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The main aim of the plan, however, was to improve public health.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Although the plan did not expand the city, it did produce some of the largest public buildings to date, like the *Paleis voor Volksvlijt*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Following Sarphati, civil engineers Jacobus van Niftrik and Jan Kalff designed an entire ring of 19th-century neighbourhoods surrounding the city's centre, with the city preserving the ownership of all land outside the 17th-century limit, thus firmly controlling development.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Most of these neighbourhoods became home to the working class.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In response to overcrowding, two plans were designed at the beginning of the 20th century which were very different from anything Amsterdam had ever seen before: *Plan Zuid* (designed by the architect Berlage) and *West*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] These plans involved the development of new neighbourhoods consisting of housing blocks for all social classes.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] After the Second World War, large new neighbourhoods were built in the western, southeastern, and northern parts of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] These new neighbourhoods were built to relieve the city's shortage of living space and give people affordable houses with modern conveniences.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhoods consisted mainly of large housing blocks located among green spaces, connected to wide roads, making the neighbourhoods accessible by motor car.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The western suburbs which were built in that period are collectively called the Westelijke Tuinsteden.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The area to the southeast of the city built during the same period is known as the Bijlmer.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has a rich architectural history.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The oldest building in Amsterdam is the Oude Kerk (English: Old Church), at the heart of the Wallen, consecrated in 1306.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The oldest wooden building is *Het Houten Huys* at the Begijnhof.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] It was constructed around 1425 and is one of only two existing wooden buildings.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] It is also one of the few examples of Gothic architecture in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The oldest stone building in the Netherlands, The Moriaan is built in 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the 16th century, wooden buildings were razed and replaced with brick ones.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] During this period, many buildings were constructed in the architectural style of the Renaissance.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Buildings of this period are very recognisable with their stepped gable façades, which is the common Dutch Renaissance style.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam quickly developed its own Renaissance architecture.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] These buildings were built according to the principles of the architect Hendrick de Keyser.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] One of the most striking buildings designed by Hendrick de Keyser is the Westerkerk.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the 17th century baroque architecture became very popular, as it was elsewhere in Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This roughly coincided with Amsterdam's Golden Age.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The leading architects of this style in Amsterdam were Jacob van Campen, Philips Vingboons and Daniel Stalpaert.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Philip Vingboons designed splendid merchants' houses throughout the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A famous building in baroque style in Amsterdam is the Royal Palace on Dam Square.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Throughout the 18th century, Amsterdam was heavily influenced by French culture.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] This is reflected in the architecture of that period.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Around 1815, architects broke with the baroque style and started building in different neo-styles.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Most Gothic style buildings date from that era and are therefore said to be built in a neo-gothic style.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] At the end of the 19th century, the Jugendstil or Art Nouveau style became popular and many new buildings were constructed in this architectural style.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Since Amsterdam expanded rapidly during this period, new buildings adjacent to the city centre were also built in this style.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The houses in the vicinity of the Museum Square in Amsterdam Oud-Zuid are an example of Jugendstil.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The last style that was popular in Amsterdam before the modern era was Art Deco.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam had its own version of the style, which was called the Amsterdamse School.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Whole districts were built in this style, such as the *Rivierenbuurt*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] A notable feature of the façades of buildings designed in Amsterdamse School is that they are highly decorated and ornate, with oddly shaped windows and doors.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The old city centre is the focal point of all the architectural styles before the end of the 19th century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Jugendstil and Georgian are mostly found outside the city centre in the neighbourhoods built in the early 20th century, although there are also some striking examples of these styles in the city centre.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Most historic buildings in the city centre and nearby are houses, such as the famous merchants' houses lining the canals.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has many parks, open spaces, and squares throughout the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Vondelpark, the largest park in the city, is located in the Oud-Zuid neighbourhood and is named after the 17th-century Amsterdam author Joost van den Vondel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Yearly, the park has around 10 million visitors.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the park is an open-air theatre, a playground, and several horeca facilities.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] In the Zuid borough, is the Beatrixpark, named after Queen Beatrix.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Between Amsterdam and Amstelveen is the Amsterdamse Bos ("Amsterdam Forest"), the largest recreational area in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Annually, almost 4.5 million people visit the park, which has a size of 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres) and is approximately three times the size of Central Park.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The Amstelpark in the Zuid borough houses the Rieker windmill, which dates to 1636.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Other parks include the Sarphatipark in the De Pijp neighbourhood, the Oosterpark in the Oost borough and the Westerpark in the Westerpark neighbourhood.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city has three beaches: Nemo Beach, Citybeach "Het stenen hoofd" (Silodam), and Blijburg, all located in the Centrum borough.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The city has many open squares (*plein* in Dutch).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] The namesake of the city as the site of the original dam, Dam Square, is the main city square and has the Royal Palace and National Monument.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Museumplein hosts various museums, including the Rijksmuseum, Van Gogh Museum, and Stedelijk Museum.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p01] Other squares include Rembrandtplein, Muntplein, Nieuwmarkt, Leidseplein, Spui and Waterlooplein.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is the financial and business capital of the Netherlands.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] A substantial number of large corporations and banks' headquarters are located in the Amsterdam area, including: AkzoNobel, Heineken International, ING Group, ABN AMRO, TomTom, Delta Lloyd Group, Booking.com and Philips.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Although many small offices remain along the historic canals, centrally based companies have increasingly relocated outside Amsterdam's city centre.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The adjoining municipality of Amstelveen is the location of KPMG International's global headquarters.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Other non-Dutch companies have chosen to settle in communities surrounding Amsterdam since they allow freehold property ownership, whereas Amsterdam retains ground rent.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange (AEX), now part of Euronext, is the world's oldest stock exchange and, due to Brexit, has overtaken LSE as the largest bourse in Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It is near Dam Square in the city centre.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Port of Amsterdam is the fourth-largest port in Europe, the 38th largest port in the world, and the second-largest port in the Netherlands by metric tons of cargo.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2014, the Port of Amsterdam had a cargo throughput of 97,4 million tons of cargo, which was mostly bulk cargo.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has the biggest cruise port in the Netherlands with more than 150 cruise ships every year.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2019, the new lock in IJmuiden opened; since then, the port has been able to grow to 125 million tonnes in capacity.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is one of the most popular tourist destinations in Europe, receiving more than 5.34 million international visitors annually; this is excluding the 16 million day-trippers visiting the city every year.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The number of visitors has been growing steadily over the past decade.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This can be attributed to an increasing number of European visitors.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Two-thirds of the hotels are located in the city's centre.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Hotels with four or five stars contribute 42% of the total beds available and 41% of the overnight stays in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The room occupation rate was 85% in 2017, up from 78% in 2006.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The majority of tourists (74%) originate from Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The largest group of non-European visitors come from the United States, accounting for 14% of the total.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Certain years have a theme in Amsterdam to attract extra tourists.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] For example, the year 2006 was designated "Rembrandt 400", to celebrate the 400th birthday of Rembrandt van Rijn.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Some hotels offer special arrangements or activities during these years.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The average number of guests per year staying at the four campsites around the city ranges from 12,000 to 65,000.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2023, the city began running a campaign to dissuade British men between the ages of 18 and 35 from coming to the city as tourists.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The ad shows young men being handcuffed by police and is part of a new campaign to clean up the city's reputation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] On 25 May 2023, in a bid to crackdown on wild tourist behaviour, the city banned weed smoking in public areas in and around the red light district.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] De Wallen, also known as Walletjes or Rosse Buurt, is a designated area for legalised prostitution and is Amsterdam's largest and best-known red-light district.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This neighbourhood has become a famous attraction for tourists.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It consists of a network of canals, streets, and alleys containing several hundred small, one-room apartments rented by sex workers who offer their services from behind a window or glass door, typically illuminated with red lights.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In recent years, the city government has been closing and repurposing the famous red-light district windows to clean up the area and reduce the amount of party and sex tourism.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Shops in Amsterdam range from large high-end department stores such as De Bijenkorf founded in 1870 to small specialty shops.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's high-end shops are found in the streets P.C.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Hooftstraat and *Cornelis Schuytstraat*, which are located in the vicinity of the Vondelpark.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] One of Amsterdam's busiest high streets is the narrow, medieval Kalverstraat in the heart of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Other shopping areas include the *Negen Straatjes* and Haarlemmerdijk and Haarlemmerstraat.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] *Negen Straatjes* are nine narrow streets within the *Grachtengordel*, the concentric canal system of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Negen Straatjes differ from other shopping districts with the presence of a large diversity of privately owned shops.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Haarlemmerstraat and Haarlemmerdijk were voted the best shopping street in the Netherlands in 2011.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] These streets have as the *Negen Straatjes* a large diversity of privately owned shops.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The city also features a large number of open-air markets such as the Albert Cuyp Market, Westerstraat-markt, Ten Katemarkt, and Dappermarkt.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Some of these markets are held daily, like the Albert Cuypmarkt and the Dappermarkt.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Others, like the Westerstraatmarkt, are held every week.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Several fashion brands and designers are based in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Fashion designers include Iris van Herpen, Mart Visser, Viktor & Rolf, Marlies Dekkers and Frans Molenaar.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Fashion models like Yfke Sturm, Doutzen Kroes and Kim Noorda started their careers in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has its garment centre in the World Fashion Center.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Fashion photographers Inez van Lamsweerde and Vinoodh Matadin were born in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] During the later part of the 16th century, Amsterdam's Rederijkerskamer (Chamber of rhetoric) organised contests between different Chambers in the reading of poetry and drama.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 1637, Schouwburg, the first theatre in Amsterdam was built, opening on 3 January 1638.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The first ballet performances in the Netherlands were given in Schouwburg in 1642 with the *Ballet of the Five Senses*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In the 18th century, French theatre became popular.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] While Amsterdam was under the influence of German music in the 19th century there were few national opera productions; the Hollandse Opera of Amsterdam was built in 1888 for the specific purpose of promoting Dutch opera.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In the 19th century, popular culture was centred on the Nes area in Amsterdam (mainly vaudeville and music-hall).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] An improved metronome was invented in 1812 by Dietrich Nikolaus Winkel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum (1885) and Stedelijk Museum (1895) were built and opened.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 1888, the Concertgebouworkest orchestra was established.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] With the 20th century came cinema, radio and television.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Though most studios are located in Hilversum and Aalsmeer, Amsterdam's influence on programming is very strong.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Many people who work in the television industry live in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Also, the headquarters of the Dutch SBS Broadcasting Group is located in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] There are also a number of cultural centers based in the city that produce public programs about the arts, sciences, politics and history, including de Balie and the John Adams Institute.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The most important museums of Amsterdam are located on the Museumplein (Museum Square), located at the southwestern side of the Rijksmuseum.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It was created in the last quarter of the 19th century on the grounds of the former World's fair.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The northeastern part of the square is bordered by the large Rijksmuseum.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In front of the Rijksmuseum on the square itself is a long, rectangular pond.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This is transformed into an ice rink in winter.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The northwestern part of the square is bordered by the Van Gogh Museum, House of Bols Cocktail & Genever Experience and Coster Diamonds.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The southwestern border of the Museum Square is the Van Baerlestraat, which is a major thoroughfare in this part of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Concertgebouw is located across this street from the square.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] To the southeast of the square are several large houses, one of which contains the American consulate.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] A parking garage can be found underneath the square, as well as a supermarket.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Museumplein is covered almost entirely with a lawn, except for the northeastern part of the square which is covered with gravel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The current appearance of the square was realised in 1999 when the square was remodelled.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The square itself is the most prominent site in Amsterdam for festivals and outdoor concerts, especially in the summer.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Plans were made in 2008 to remodel the square again because many inhabitants of Amsterdam are not happy with its current appearance.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum possesses the largest and most important collection of classical Dutch art.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Its collection consists of nearly one million objects.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The artist most associated with Amsterdam is Rembrandt, whose work, and the work of his pupils, is displayed in the Rijksmuseum.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Rembrandt's masterpiece *The Night Watch* is one of the top pieces of art in the museum.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It also houses paintings from artists like Bartholomeus van der Helst, Johannes Vermeer, Frans Hals, Ferdinand Bol, Albert Cuyp, Jacob van Ruisdael and Paulus Potter.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Aside from paintings, the collection consists of a large variety of decorative art.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This ranges from Delftware to giant doll-houses from the 17th century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The architect of the gothic revival building was P.J.H.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The museum underwent a 10-year, 375 million euro renovation starting in 2003.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The full collection was reopened to the public on 13 April 2013.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum has remained the most visited museum in Amsterdam with 2.4 million visitors in 2024.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Van Gogh lived in Amsterdam for a short while and there is a museum dedicated to his work.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The museum is housed in one of the few modern buildings in this area of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The building was designed by Gerrit Rietveld.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This building is where the permanent collection is displayed.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] A new building was added to the museum in 1999.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This building, known as the performance wing, was designed by Japanese architect Kisho Kurokawa.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Its purpose is to house temporary exhibitions of the museum.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Some of Van Gogh's most famous paintings, like *The Potato Eaters* and *Sunflowers*, are in the collection.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Van Gogh museum is the second most visited museum in Amsterdam, not far behind the Rijksmuseum in terms of the number of visits, being approximately 1.8 million in 2024.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Next to the Van Gogh Museum stands the Stedelijk Museum.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This is Amsterdam's most important museum of modern art.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The museum is as old as the square it borders and was opened in 1895.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The permanent collection consists of works of art from artists like Piet Mondrian, Karel Appel, and Kazimir Malevich.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] After renovations lasting several years, the museum opened in September 2012 with a new composite extension that has been called 'The Bathtub' due to its resemblance to one.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam contains many other museums throughout the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The modern-styled Nemo is dedicated to child-friendly science exhibitions.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's musical culture includes a large collection of songs that treat the city nostalgically and lovingly.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The 1949 song "Aan de Amsterdamse grachten" ("On the canals of Amsterdam") was performed and recorded by many artists, including John Kraaijkamp Sr.; the best-known version is probably that by Wim Sonneveld (1962).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In the 1950s Johnny Jordaan rose to fame with "Geef mij maar Amsterdam" ("I prefer Amsterdam"), which praises the city above all others (explicitly Paris); Jordaan sang especially about his own neighbourhood, the Jordaan ("Bij ons in de Jordaan").
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Colleagues and contemporaries of Johnny include Tante Leen and Manke Nelis.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Another notable Amsterdam song is "Amsterdam" by Jacques Brel (1964).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] A 2011 poll by Amsterdam newspaper *Het Parool* that Trio Bier's "Oude Wolf" was voted "Amsterdams lijflied".
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Notable Amsterdam bands from the modern era include the Osdorp Posse and the Ex.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] AFAS Live (formerly known as the Heineken Music Hall) is a concert hall located near the Johan Cruyff Arena (known as the Amsterdam Arena until 2018).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Its main purpose is to serve as a podium for pop concerts for big audiences.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Many famous international artists have performed there.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Two other notable venues, Paradiso and the Melkweg are located near the Leidseplein.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Both focus on broad programming, ranging from indie rock to hip-hop, R&B, and other popular genres.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Other subcultural music venues are OCCII, OT301, De Nieuwe Anita, Winston Kingdom, and Zaal 100.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Jazz has a strong following in Amsterdam, with the Bimhuis being the premier venue.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2012, Ziggo Dome was opened, also near Amsterdam Arena, a state-of-the-art indoor music arena.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] AFAS Live is also host to many electronic dance music festivals, alongside many other venues.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Armin van Buuren and Tiesto, some of the world's leading Trance DJs hail from the Netherlands and frequently perform in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Each year in October, the city hosts the Amsterdam Dance Event (ADE) which is one of the leading electronic music conferences and one of the biggest club festivals for electronic music in the world, attracting over 350,000 visitors each year.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Another popular dance festival is 5daysoff, which takes place in the venues Paradiso and Melkweg.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In the summertime, there are several big outdoor dance parties in or nearby Amsterdam, such as Awakenings, Dance Valley, Mystery Land, Loveland, A Day at the Park, Welcome to the Future, and Valtifest.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has a world-class symphony orchestra, the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Their home is the Concertgebouw, which is across the Van Baerlestraat from the Museum Square.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It is considered by critics to be a concert hall with some of the best acoustics in the world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The building contains three halls, Grote Zaal, Kleine Zaal, and Spiegelzaal.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Some nine hundred concerts and other events per year take place in the Concertgebouw, for a public of over 700,000, making it one of the most-visited concert halls in the world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The opera house of Amsterdam is located adjacent to the city hall.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Therefore, the two buildings combined are often called the Stopera, (a word originally coined by protesters against its very construction: *Stop the Opera[-house]*).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This huge modern complex, opened in 1986, lies in the former Jewish neighbourhood at *Waterlooplein* next to the river Amstel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The *Stopera* is the home base of Dutch National Opera, Dutch National Ballet and the Holland Symfonia.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Muziekgebouw aan 't IJ is a concert hall, which is located in the IJ near the central station.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Its concerts perform mostly modern classical music.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Located adjacent to it, is the *Bimhuis*, a concert hall for improvised and jazz music.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has three main theatre buildings.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Stadsschouwburg at the Leidseplein is the home base of Toneelgroep Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Most plays are performed in the Grote Zaal (Great Hall).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The normal program of events encompasses all sorts of theatrical forms.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2009, the new hall of the Stadsschouwburg Amsterdam, Toneelgroep Amsterdam, and Melkweg opened, and the renovation of the front end of the theatre was ready.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Dutch National Opera and Ballet (formerly known as *Het Muziektheater*), dating from 1986, is the principal opera house and home to Dutch National Opera and Dutch National Ballet.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Royal Theatre Carré was built as a permanent circus theatre in 1887 and is currently mainly used for musicals, cabaret performances, and pop concerts.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The recently re-opened DeLaMar Theater houses more commercial plays and musicals.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] A new theatre has also moved into the Amsterdam scene in 2014, joining other established venues: Theater Amsterdam is located in the west part of Amsterdam, on the Danzigerkade.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It is housed in a modern building with a panoramic view over the harbour.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The theatre is the first-ever purpose-built venue to showcase a single play entitled ANNE, the play based on Anne Frank's life.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] On the east side of town, there is a small theatre in a converted bathhouse, the Badhuistheater.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The theatre often has English programming.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Netherlands has a tradition of cabaret or *kleinkunst*, which combines music, storytelling, commentary, theatre, and comedy.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Cabaret dates back to the 1930s and artists like Wim Kan, Wim Sonneveld, and Toon Hermans were pioneers of this form of art in the Netherlands.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In Amsterdam are the Kleinkunstacademie (English: Cabaret Academy) and Nederlied Kleinkunstkoor (English: Cabaret Choir).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Contemporary popular artists are Youp van 't Hek, Freek de Jonge, Herman Finkers, Hans Teeuwen, Theo Maassen, Herman van Veen, Najib Amhali, Raoul Heertje, Jörgen Raymann, Brigitte Kaandorp and Comedytrain.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The English-spoken comedy scene was established with the founding of Boom Chicago in 1993.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] They have their own theatre at Leidseplein.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is famous for its vibrant and diverse nightlife.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] They range from large and modern to small and cosy.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The typical *Bruine Kroeg* (brown *café*) breathes a more old-fashioned atmosphere with dimmed lights, candles, and somewhat older clientele.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] These brown cafés mostly offer a wide range of local and international artisanal beers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Most *cafés* have terraces in summertime.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] A common sight on the Leidseplein during summer is a square full of terraces packed with people drinking beer or wine.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Many restaurants can be found in Amsterdam as well.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Since Amsterdam is a multicultural city, a lot of different ethnic restaurants can be found.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Restaurants range from being rather luxurious and expensive to being ordinary and affordable.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam also possesses many discothèques.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The two main nightlife areas for tourists are the Leidseplein and the Rembrandtplein.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Paradiso, Melkweg and Sugar Factory are cultural centres, which turn into discothèques on some nights.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2008, there were 140 festivals and events in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] During the same year, Amsterdam was designated as the World Book Capital for one year by UNESCO.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] On Koningsdag—which is held each year on 27 April—hundreds of thousands of people travel to Amsterdam to celebrate with the city's residents.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The entire city becomes overcrowded with people buying products from the *free market*, or visiting one of the many music concerts.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The yearly Holland Festival attracts international artists and visitors from all over Europe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Gay Pride is a yearly local LGBT parade of boats in Amsterdam's canals, held on the first Saturday in August.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The annual Uitmarkt is a three-day cultural event at the start of the cultural season in late August.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It offers previews of many different artists, such as musicians and poets, who perform on podia.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is home of the *Eredivisie* football club AFC Ajax.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The stadium Johan Cruyff Arena is the home of Ajax.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It is located in the south-east of the city next to the new Amsterdam Bijlmer ArenA railway station.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Before moving to their current location in 1996, Ajax played their regular matches in the now demolished De Meer Stadion in the eastern part of the city or in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 1928, Amsterdam hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Olympic Stadium built for the occasion has been completely restored and is now used for cultural and sporting events, such as the Amsterdam Marathon.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 1920, Amsterdam assisted in hosting some of the sailing events for the Summer Olympics held in neighbouring Antwerp, Belgium by hosting events at Buiten IJ.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] They had also made a bid to host the 1952 and 1992 Summer Olympics but lost to Helsinki and Barcelona.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The city holds the Dam to Dam Run, a 16 km (10 mi) race from Amsterdam to Zaandam, as well as the Amsterdam Marathon.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The ice hockey team Amstel Tijgers plays in the Jaap Eden ice rink.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The team competes in the Dutch Ice Hockey Premier League.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Speed skating championships have been held on the 400-meter lane of this ice rink.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam holds two American football franchises: the Amsterdam Crusaders and the Amsterdam Panthers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Pirates baseball team competes in the Dutch Major League.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] There are three field hockey teams: Amsterdam, Pinoké, and Hurley, who play their matches around the Wagener Stadium in the nearby city of Amstelveen.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The basketball team MyGuide Amsterdam competes in the Dutch premier division and play their games in the Sporthallen Zuid.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] There is one rugby club in Amsterdam, which also hosts sports training classes such as RTC (Rugby Talenten Centrum or Rugby Talent Centre) and the National Rugby Stadium.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Since 1999, the city of Amsterdam honours the best sportsmen and women at the Amsterdam Sports Awards.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Boxer Raymond Joval and field hockey midfielder Carole Thate were the first to receive the awards, in 1999.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam hosted the World Gymnaestrada in 1991 and will do so again in 2023.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The city of Amsterdam is a municipality under the Dutch Municipalities Act.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It is governed by a directly elected municipal council, a municipal executive, and a mayor.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Since 1981, the municipality of Amsterdam has gradually been divided into semi-autonomous boroughs, called *stadsdelen* or 'districts'.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Over time, a total of 15 boroughs were created.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] As with all Dutch municipalities, Amsterdam is governed by a directly elected municipal council, a municipal executive and a government appointed mayor (*burgemeester*).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The mayor is a member of the municipal executive board but also has individual responsibilities in maintaining public order.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] She replaces Eberhard van der Laan (Labour Party) who was the Mayor of Amsterdam from 2010 until his death in October 2017.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] After the 2014 municipal council elections, a governing majority of D66, VVD and SP was formed – the first coalition without the Labour Party since World War II.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Next to the mayor, the municipal executive consists of eight *wethouders* ('alderpersons') appointed by the municipal council: four D66 alderpersons, two VVD alderpersons and two SP alderpersons.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] On 18 September 2017, it was announced by Eberhard van der Laan in an open letter to Amsterdam citizens that Kajsa Ollongren would take up his office as acting Mayor of Amsterdam with immediate effect due to ill health.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Ollongren was succeeded as acting Mayor by Eric van der Burg on 26 October 2017 and by Jozias van Aartsen on 4 December 2017.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Unlike most other Dutch municipalities, Amsterdam is subdivided into seven boroughs, called *stadsdelen* or 'districts', and the urban area of Weesp.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This system was gradually implemented in the 1980s to improve local governance.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The boroughs are responsible for many activities that had previously been run by the central city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2010, the number of Amsterdam boroughs reached fifteen.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Fourteen of those had their own district council (*deelraad*), elected by a popular vote.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The fifteenth, Westpoort, covers the harbour of Amsterdam and has very few residents.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Therefore, it was governed by the central municipal council.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Under the borough system, municipal decisions are made at the borough level, except for those affairs on the whole city such as major infrastructure projects, which are the jurisdiction of the central municipal authorities.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2010, the borough system was restructured, in which many smaller boroughs merged into larger boroughs.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2014, under a reform of the Dutch Municipalities Act, the Amsterdam boroughs lost much of their autonomous status, as their district councils were abolished.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The municipal council of Amsterdam voted to maintain the borough system by replacing the district councils with smaller, but still directly elected district committees (*bestuurscommissies*).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Under a municipal ordinance, the new district committees were granted responsibilities through the delegation of regulatory and executive powers by the central municipal council.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] "Amsterdam" is usually understood to refer to the municipality of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Colloquially, some areas within the municipality, such as the town of Durgerdam, may not be considered part of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Department for Research and Statistics uses a fourth conurbation, namely the *Stadsregio Amsterdam* ('City Region of Amsterdam').
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The city region is similar to Greater Amsterdam but includes the municipalities of Zaanstad and Wormerland.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The smallest of these areas is the municipality of Amsterdam with a population of about 870,000 in 2021.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The larger conurbation had a population of over one million.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It includes the municipalities of Zaanstad, Wormerland, Oostzaan, Diemen, and Amstelveen only, as well as the municipality of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Greater Amsterdam includes 15 municipalities and had a population of 1,400,000 in 2021.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Though much larger in area, the population of this area is only slightly larger, because the definition excludes the relatively populous municipality of Zaanstad.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The largest area by population, the Metropolitan Region Amsterdam (Dutch: Metropoolregio Amsterdam), has a population of 2,33 million.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It includes for instance Zaanstad, Wormerland, Muiden, Abcoude, Haarlem, Almere and Lelystad but excludes Graft-De Rijp.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is part of the conglomerate metropolitan area Randstad, with a total population of 6,659,300 inhabitants.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Of these various metropolitan area configurations, only the *Stadsregio Amsterdam* (City Region of Amsterdam) has a formal governmental status.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Its responsibilities include regional spatial planning and metropolitan public transport concessions.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Under the Dutch Constitution, Amsterdam is the capital of the Netherlands.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Since the 1983 constitutional revision, the constitution mentions "Amsterdam" and "capital" in chapter 2, article 32: The king's confirmation by oath and his coronation take place in "the capital Amsterdam" ("*de hoofdstad Amsterdam*").
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Previous versions of the constitution only mentioned "the city of Amsterdam" ("*de stad Amsterdam*").
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] For a royal investiture, therefore, the States General of the Netherlands (the Dutch Parliament) meets for a ceremonial joint session in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The ceremony traditionally takes place at the Nieuwe Kerk on Dam Square, immediately after the former monarch has signed the act of abdication at the nearby Royal Palace of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Normally, however, the Parliament sits in The Hague, the city which has historically been the seat of the Dutch government, the Dutch monarchy, and the Dutch supreme court.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Foreign embassies are also located in The Hague.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The coat of arms of Amsterdam is composed of several historical elements.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] First and centre are three St Andrew's crosses, aligned in a vertical band on the city's shield (although Amsterdam's patron saint was Saint Nicholas).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] These St Andrew's crosses can also be found on the city shields of neighbours Amstelveen and Ouder-Amstel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This part of the coat of arms is the basis of the flag of Amsterdam, flown by the city government, but also as civil ensign for ships registered in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Second is the Imperial Crown of Austria.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 1489, out of gratitude for services and loans, Maximilian I awarded Amsterdam the right to adorn its coat of arms with the king's crown.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Then, in 1508, this was replaced with Maximilian's imperial crown when he was crowned Holy Roman Emperor.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In the early years of the 17th century, Maximilian's crown in Amsterdam's coat of arms was again replaced, this time with the crown of Emperor Rudolph II, a crown that became the Imperial Crown of Austria.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The lions date from the late 16th century, when the city and province became part of the Republic of the Seven United Netherlands.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Last came the city's official motto: *Heldhaftig, Vastberaden, Barmhartig* ("Heroic, Determined, Merciful"), bestowed on the city in 1947 by Queen Wilhelmina, in recognition of the city's bravery during the Second World War.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Currently, there are sixteen tram routes and five metro routes.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] All are operated by the municipal public transport operator Gemeentelijk Vervoerbedrijf (GVB), which also runs the city bus network.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Four fare-free GVB ferries carry pedestrians and cyclists across the IJ lake to the borough of Amsterdam-Noord, and two fare-charging ferries run east and west along the harbour.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] There are also privately operated water taxis, a water bus, a boat-sharing operation, electric rental boats, and canal cruises, that transport people along Amsterdam's waterways.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Regional buses, and some suburban buses, are operated by Connexxion and EBS.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] International coach services are provided by FlixBus and BlaBlaCar Bus.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] To facilitate easier transport to the centre of Amsterdam, the city has various P+R Locations where people can park their car at an affordable price and transfer to one of the numerous public transport lines.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam was intended in 1932 to be the hub, a kind of Kilometre Zero, of the highway system of the Netherlands, with freeways numbered One to Eight planned to originate from the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The outbreak of the Second World War and shifting priorities led to the current situation, where only roads A1, A2, and A4 originate from Amsterdam according to the original plan.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The A3 to Rotterdam was cancelled in 1970 to conserve the Groene Hart.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Road A8, leading north to Zaandam and the A10 Ringroad were opened between 1968 and 1974.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Besides the A1, A2, A4 and A8, several freeways, such as the A7 and A6, carry traffic mainly bound for Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The A10 ringroad surrounding the city connects Amsterdam with the Dutch national network of freeways.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Interchanges on the A10 allow cars to enter the city by transferring to one of the 18 *city roads*, numbered S101 through to S118.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] These city roads are regional roads without grade separation, and sometimes without a central reservation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The S100 *Centrumring* is a smaller ring road circumnavigating the city's centre.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In the city centre, driving a car is discouraged.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Parking fees are expensive, and many streets are closed to cars or are one-way.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The local government sponsors carsharing and carpooling initiatives such as *Autodelen* and *Meerijden.nu*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The local government has also started removing parking spaces in the city in 2019, with the goal of removing 10,000 spaces (roughly 1,500 per year) by 2025.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is served by ten stations of the Nederlandse Spoorwegen (Dutch Railways).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Five are intercity stops: Sloterdijk, Zuid, Amstel, Bijlmer ArenA and Amsterdam Centraal.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The stations for local services are: Lelylaan, RAI, Holendrecht, Muiderpoort and Science Park.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Centraal is also an international railway station.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] From the station, there are regular services to destinations such as Austria, Belgium, Czech Republic, France, Germany, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Among these trains are international trains of the Nederlandse Spoorwegen and Deutsche Bahn to Berlin, Eurostar services to Antwerp, Brussels, Paris and London and ICE services to Cologne and Frankfurt.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Airport Schiphol is less than 20 minutes by train from Amsterdam Centraal station and is served by domestic and international intercity trains, such as Eurostar and EuroCity.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Schiphol is the largest airport in the Netherlands, the third-largest in Europe, and the 14th-largest in the world in terms of passengers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] It handles over 68 million passengers per year and is the home base of four airlines, KLM, Transavia, Martinair and Arkefly.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] As of 2014, Schiphol was the fifth busiest airport in the world measured by international passenger numbers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This airport is 4 meters below sea level.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Although Schiphol is internationally known as Amsterdam Schiphol Airport it lies in the neighbouring municipality of Haarlemmermeer, southwest of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Rotterdam The Hague Airport, a smaller international airport, is also within an hour's drive of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is one of the most bicycle-friendly large cities in the world and is a centre of bicycle culture with good facilities for cyclists such as bike paths and bike racks, and several guarded bike storage garages (*fietsenstalling*) which can be used.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] According to the most recent figures published by the Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS), in 2015 the 442,693 households (850,000 residents) in Amsterdam together owned 847,000 bicycles – 1.91 bicycles per household.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Theft is widespread—in 2011, about 83,000 bicycles were stolen in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Bicycles are used by all socio-economic groups because of their convenience, Amsterdam's small size, the 400 km (249 mi) of bike paths, the flat terrain, and the inconvenience of driving an automobile.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has two universities: the University of Amsterdam (*Universiteit van Amsterdam*, UvA), and the *Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam* (VU).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The University of Amsterdam is home to Room for Discussion, an independent interview platform that has welcomed a variety of prominent guests including Christine Lagarde, Mario Draghi, Charles Michel, Rob Bauer, and Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Other institutions for higher education include an art school – Gerrit Rietveld Academie, a university of applied sciences – the Hogeschool van Amsterdam, and the Amsterdamse Hogeschool voor de Kunsten.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's International Institute of Social History is one of the world's largest documentary and research institutions concerning social history, and especially the history of the labour movement.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's Hortus Botanicus, founded in the early 17th century, is one of the oldest botanical gardens in the world, with many old and rare specimens, among them the coffee plant that served as the parent for the entire coffee culture in Central and South America.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] There are over 200 primary schools in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Some of these primary schools base their teachings on particular pedagogic theories like the various Montessori schools.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The biggest Montessori high school in Amsterdam is the Montessori Lyceum Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Many schools, however, are based on religion.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] This used to be primarily Roman Catholicism and various Protestant denominations, but with the influx of Muslim immigrants, there has been a rise in the number of Islamic schools.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Jewish schools can be found in the southern suburbs of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is noted for having five independent grammar schools (Dutch: gymnasia), the Vossius Gymnasium, Barlaeus Gymnasium, St.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Ignatius Gymnasium, Het 4e Gymnasium and the Cygnus Gymnasium where a classical curriculum including Latin and classical Greek is taught.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Though believed until recently by many to be an anachronistic and elitist concept that would soon die out, the gymnasia have recently experienced a revival, leading to the formation of a fourth and fifth grammar school in which the three aforementioned schools participate.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Most secondary schools in Amsterdam offer a variety of different levels of education in the same school.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The city also has various colleges ranging from art and design to politics and economics which are mostly also available for students coming from other countries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is a prominent centre for national and international media.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is home to the second-largest Dutch commercial TV group SBS Broadcasting Group, consisting of TV stations SBS6, Net5, and Veronica.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] However, Amsterdam is not considered 'the media city of the Netherlands'.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The town of Hilversum, 30 km (19 mi) south-east of Amsterdam, has been crowned with this unofficial title.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Hilversum is the principal centre for radio and television broadcasting in the Netherlands.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Radio Netherlands, heard worldwide via shortwave radio since the 1920s, is also based there.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Hilversum is home to an extensive complex of audio and television studios belonging to the national broadcast production company NOS, as well as to the studios and offices of all the Dutch public broadcasting organisations and many commercial TV production companies.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2012, the music video for "Live My Life" by Far East Movement was filmed in various parts of Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Several movies have been filmed in Amsterdam, including the James Bond film *Diamonds Are Forever*, *Ocean's Twelve*, *Girl with a Pearl Earring*, *Kidnapping Mr.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Heineken*, *Layer Cake* and *The Hitman's Bodyguard*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is also featured in John Green's book *The Fault in Our Stars*, which was made into a film that also partly takes place in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] In 2003, the British drama series *Bad Girls* filmed scenes on location in Amsterdam.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] The scenes shows the male officers on a weekend trip in the red light district where they encounter escapee Shell Dockley and return her to the UK.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam appears as a multiplayer map in *Modern Warfare II* under the name Breenbergh Hotel.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam also appears in *Black Ops Cold War* in an update, having players fight through the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] From the late 1960s onwards many buildings in Amsterdam have been squatted both for housing and for use as social centres.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/amsterdam-p02] A number of these squats have legalised and become well known, such as OCCII, OT301, Paradiso and Vrankrijk.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara was historically known as Ancyra and Angora.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Serving as the capital of the ancient Celtic state of Galatia (280–64 BC), and later of the Roman province with the same name (25 BC–7th century), Ankara has various Hattian, Hittite, Lydian, Phrygian, Galatian, Greek, Persian, Roman, Byzantine, and Ottoman archeological sites.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Ottomans made the city the capital of the Anatolia Eyalet (1393 – late 15th century), the Angora Eyalet (1827–1864), and the Angora Vilayet (1867–1922).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] On 23 April 1920, the Grand National Assembly of Turkey was established in Ankara, which became the headquarters of the Turkish National Movement during the Turkish War of Independence.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara became the new Turkish capital upon the establishment of the Republic on 29 October 1923, succeeding the former Ottoman capital Istanbul following the fall of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The historical center of Ankara is a rocky hill rising 150 m (500 ft) over the left bank of the Ankara River, a tributary of the Sakarya River.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The hill remains crowned by the ruins of Ankara Castle.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Few of its outworks have survived, but there are well-preserved examples of Roman and Ottoman architecture throughout the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The government is a prominent employer, but Ankara is also an important commercial and industrial city located at the center of Turkey's road and railway networks.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city gave its name to the Angora wool shorn from Angora rabbits, the long-haired Angora goat (the source of mohair), and the Angora cat.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The area is also known for its pears, honey and Muscat grapes.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Although situated in one of the driest regions of Turkey and surrounded mostly by steppe vegetation (except for the forested areas on the southern periphery), Ankara can be considered a green city in terms of green areas per inhabitant, at 72 square meters (775 square feet) per head.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Home to numerous universities, Ankara is among the top 100 science and technology clusters in the world.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The orthography of the name *Ankara* has varied over the ages.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It has been identified with the Hittite cult center *Ankuwaš*, although this remains a matter of debate.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In classical antiquity and during the medieval period, the city was known as *Ánkyra* (Ἄγκυρα, lit.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 'anchor') in Greek and *Ancyra* in Latin; the Galatian Celtic name was probably a similar variant.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Following its annexation by the Seljuk Turks in 1073, the city became known in many European languages as *Angora*; it was also known in Ottoman Turkish as *Engürü* (انگورو).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The form "Angora" is preserved in the names of breeds of many different kinds of animals, and in the names of several locations in the US (see Angora).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] , which is considered as the city's symbol.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The oldest settlements in and around the city center of Ankara belonged to the Hattic civilization which existed during the Bronze Age and was gradually absorbed c.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 2000 – 1700 BC by the Indo-European Hittites.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city grew significantly in size and importance under the Phrygians starting around 1000 BC, and experienced a large expansion following the mass migration from Gordion, (the capital of Phrygia), after an earthquake which severely damaged that city around that time.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In Phrygian tradition, King Midas was venerated as the founder of Ancyra, but Pausanias mentions that the city was actually far older, which accords with present archeological knowledge.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Phrygian rule was succeeded first by Lydian and later by Persian rule, though the strongly Phrygian character of the peasantry remained, as evidenced by the gravestones of the much later Roman period.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Persian sovereignty lasted until the Persians' defeat at the hands of Alexander the Great who conquered the city in 333 BC.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Alexander came from Gordion to Ankara and stayed in the city for a short period.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After his death at Babylon in 323 BC and the subsequent division of his empire among his generals, Ankara, and its environs fell into the share of Antigonus.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] By that time, the city also took its name Ἄγκυρα (*Ánkyra*, meaning *anchor* in Greek) which, in slightly modified form, provides the modern name of *Ankara*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 278 BC, the city, along with the rest of central Anatolia, was occupied by a Celtic group, the Galatians (Gauls), who were the first to make Ankara one of their main tribal centers, the headquarters of the Tectosages tribe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Other centers were Pessinus, today's Ballıhisar, for the Trocmi tribe, and Tavium, to the east of Ankara, for the Tolistobogii tribe.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Celtic element was probably relatively small in numbers; a warrior aristocracy which ruled over Phrygian-speaking peasants.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] However, the Celtic language continued to be spoken in Galatia for many centuries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Jerome, a native of Dalmatia, observed that the language spoken around Ankara was very similar to that being spoken in the northwest of the Roman world near Trier.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city was subsequently passed under the control of the Roman Empire.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 25 BC, Emperor Augustus raised it to the status of a *polis* and made it the capital city of the Roman province of Galatia.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara is famous for the *Monumentum Ancyranum* (*Temple of Augustus and Rome*) which contains the official record of the *Acts of Augustus*, known as the *Res Gestae Divi Augusti*, an inscription cut in marble on the walls of this temple.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The ruins of Ancyra still furnish today valuable bas-reliefs, inscriptions and other architectural fragments.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Two other Galatian tribal centers, Tavium near Yozgat, and Pessinus (Balhisar) to the west, near Sivrihisar, continued to be reasonably important settlements in the Roman period, but it was Ancyra that grew into a grand metropolis.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] An estimated 200,000 people lived in Ancyra in good times during the Roman Empire, a far greater number than was to be the case from after the fall of the Roman Empire until the early 20th century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The small Ankara River ran through the center of the Roman town.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It has now been covered and diverted, but it formed the northern boundary of the old town during the Roman, Byzantine and Ottoman periods. Çankaya, the rim of the majestic hill to the south of the present city center, stood well outside the Roman city, but may have been a summer resort.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In the 19th century, the remains of at least one Roman villa or large house were still standing not far from where the Çankaya Presidential Residence stands today.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] To the west, the Roman city extended until the area of the Gençlik Park and Railway Station, while on the southern side of the hill, it may have extended downward as far as the site presently occupied by Hacettepe University.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It was thus a sizeable city by any standards and much larger than the Roman towns of Gaul or Britannia.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ancyra's importance rested on the fact that it was the junction point where the roads in northern Anatolia running north–south and east–west intersected, giving it major strategic importance for Rome's eastern frontier.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The great imperial road running east passed through Ankara and a succession of emperors and their armies came this way.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] They were not the only ones to use the Roman highway network, which was equally convenient for invaders.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In the second half of the 3rd century, Ancyra was invaded in rapid succession by the Goths coming from the west (who rode far into the heart of Cappadocia, taking slaves and pillaging) and later by the Arabs.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] For about a decade, the town was one of the western outposts of one of Palmyrean empress Zenobia in the Syrian Desert, who took advantage of a period of weakness and disorder in the Roman Empire to set up a short-lived state of her own.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The town was reincorporated into the Roman Empire under Emperor Aurelian in 272.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The tetrarchy, a system of multiple (up to four) emperors introduced by Diocletian (284–305), seems to have engaged in a substantial program of rebuilding and of road construction from Ancyra westwards to Germe and Dorylaeum (now Eskişehir).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In its heyday, Roman Ancyra was a large market and trading center but it also functioned as a major administrative capital, where a high official ruled from the city's Praetorium, a large administrative palace or office.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] During the 3rd century, life in Ancyra, as in other Anatolian towns, seems to have become somewhat militarized in response to the invasions and instability of the town.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city is well known during the 4th century as a center of Christian activity (see also below), due to frequent imperial visits, and through the letters of the pagan scholar Libanius.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Bishop Marcellus of Ancyra and Basil of Ancyra were active in the theological controversies of their day, and the city was the site of no fewer than three church synods in 314, 358 and 375, the latter two in favor of Arianism.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city was visited by Emperor Constans I (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 361–363) during his Persian campaign in 362, and Julian's successor Jovian (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 363–364) in winter 363/364 (he entered his consulship while in the city).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After Jovian's death soon after, Valentinian I (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 364–375) was acclaimed emperor at Ancyra, and in the next year his brother Valens (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 364–378) used Ancyra as his base against the usurper Procopius.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] When the province of Galatia was divided sometime in 396/99, Ancyra remained the civil capital of Galatia I, as well as its ecclesiastical center (metropolitan see).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 383–408) frequently used the city as his summer residence, and some information about the ecclesiastical affairs of the city during the early 5th century is found in the works of Palladius of Galatia and Nilus of Ancyra.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 479, the rebel Marcian attacked the city, without being able to capture it.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 610/11, Comentiolus, brother of Emperor Phocas (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 602–610), launched his own unsuccessful rebellion in the city against Heraclius (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ten years later, in 620 or more likely 622, it was captured by the Sassanid Persians during the Byzantine–Sassanid War of 602–628.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Although the city returned to Byzantine hands after the end of the war, the Persian presence left traces in the city's archeology, and likely began the process of its transformation from a late antique city to a medieval fortified settlement.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 654, the city, also known in Arabic sources as *Qalat as-Salasil* ("fortress of the chains"), was captured for the first time by the Arabs of the Rashidun Caliphate, under Muawiyah, the future founder of the Umayyad Caliphate.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] At about the same time, the themes were established in Anatolia, and Ancyra became capital of the Opsician Theme, which was the largest and most important theme until it was split up under Emperor Constantine V (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 741–775); Ancyra then became the capital of the new Bucellarian Theme.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city was captured at least temporarily by the Umayyad prince Maslama ibn Hisham in 739/40, the last of the Umayyads' territorial gains from the Byzantine Empire.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ancyra was attacked without success by Abbasid forces in 776 and in 798/99.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 802–811) strengthened its fortifications, a fact which probably saved it from sack during the large-scale invasion of Anatolia by Caliph Harun al-Rashid in the next year.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Arab sources report that Harun and his successor al-Ma'mun (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 813–833) took the city, but this information is later invention.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 838, however, during the Amorium campaign, the armies of Caliph al-Mu'tasim (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 833–842) converged and met at the city; abandoned by its inhabitants, Ancara was razed to the ground, before the Arab armies went on to besiege and destroy Amorium reaching as far as Smyrna.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 842–867) came to the city during a campaign against the Arabs, and ordered its fortifications restored.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 872, the city was menaced, but not taken, by the Paulicians under Chrysocheir.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The last Arab raid to reach the city was undertaken in 931, by the Abbasid governor of Tarsus, Thamal al-Dulafi, but the city again was not captured.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Early Christian martyrs of Ancyra, about whom little is known, included Proklos and Hilarios who were natives of the otherwise unknown nearby village of Kallippi, and suffered repression under the emperor Trajan (98–117).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In the 280s we hear of Philumenos, a Christian corn merchant from southern Anatolia, being captured and martyred in Ankara, and Eustathius.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] As in other Roman towns, the reign of Diocletian marked the culmination of the persecution of the Christians.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 303, Ancyra was one of the towns where the co-emperors Diocletian and his deputy Galerius launched their anti-Christian persecution.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In Ancyra, their first target was the 38-year-old Bishop of the town, whose name was Clement.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Clement's life describes how he was taken to Rome, then sent back, and forced to undergo many interrogations and hardship before he, and his brother, and various companions were put to death.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Clement can be found today in a building just off Işıklar Caddesi in the Ulus district.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Quite possibly this marks the site where Clement was originally buried.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Four years later, a doctor of the town named Plato and his brother Antiochus also became celebrated martyrs under Galerius.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Theodotus of Ancyra is also venerated as a saint.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] However, the persecution proved unsuccessful and in 314 Ancyra was the center of an important council of the early church; its 25 disciplinary canons constitute one of the most important documents in the early history of the administration of the Sacrament of Penance.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The synod also considered ecclesiastical policy for the reconstruction of the Christian Church after the persecutions, and in particular the treatment of *lapsi*—Christians who had given in to forced paganism (sacrifices) to avoid martyrdom during these persecutions.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Though paganism was probably tottering in Ancyra in Clement's day, it may still have been the majority religion.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Twenty years later, Christianity and monotheism had taken its place.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ancyra quickly turned into a Christian city, with a life dominated by monks and priests and theological disputes.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The town council or senate gave way to the bishop as the main local figurehead.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] During the middle of the 4th century, Ancyra was involved in the complex theological disputes over the nature of Christ, and a form of Arianism seems to have originated there.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 362–363, Emperor Julian passed through Ancyra on his way to an ill-fated campaign against the Persians, and according to Christian sources, engaged in a persecution of various holy men.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The stone base for a statue, with an inscription describing Julian as "Lord of the whole world from the British Ocean to the barbarian nations", can still be seen, built into the eastern side of the inner circuit of the walls of Ankara Castle.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Column of Julian which was erected in honor of the emperor's visit to the city in 362 still stands today.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 375, Arian bishops met at Ancyra and deposed several bishops, among them St.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In the late 4th century, Ancyra became something of an imperial holiday resort.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After Constantinople became the East Roman capital, emperors in the 4th and 5th centuries would retire from the humid summer weather on the Bosporus to the drier mountain atmosphere of Ancyra.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Theodosius II (408–450) kept his court in Ancyra in the summers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Laws issued in Ancyra testify to the time they spent there.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Metropolis of Ancyra continued to be a residential see of the Eastern Orthodox Church until the 20th century, with about 40,000 faithful, mostly Turkish-speaking, but that situation ended as a result of the 1923 Convention Concerning the Exchange of Greek and Turkish Populations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The earlier Armenian genocide put an end to the residential eparchy of Ancyra of the Armenian Catholic Church, which had been established in 1850.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It is also a titular metropolis of the Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Both the Ancient Byzantine Metropolitan archbishopric and the 'modern' Armenian eparchy are now listed by the Catholic Church as titular sees, with separate apostolic successions.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After the Battle of Manzikert in 1071, the Seljuk Turks overran much of Anatolia.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] By 1073, the Turkish settlers had reached the vicinity of Ancyra, and the city was captured shortly after, at the latest by the time of the rebellion of Nikephoros Melissenos in 1081.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 1101, when the Crusade under Raymond IV of Toulouse arrived, the city had been under Danishmend control for some time.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Crusaders captured the city, and handed it over to the Byzantine emperor Alexios I Komnenos (r.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Byzantine rule did not last long, and the city was captured by the Seljuk Sultanate of Rum at some unknown point; in 1127, it returned to Danishmend control until 1143, when the Seljuks of Rum retook it.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After the Battle of Köse Dağ in 1243, in which the Mongols defeated the Seljuks, most of Anatolia became part of the dominion of the Mongols.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Taking advantage of Seljuk decline, a semi-religious cast of craftsmen and trade people named *Ahiler* chose Angora as their independent city-state in 1290.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Orhan, the second Bey of the Ottoman Empire, captured the city in 1356.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Timur defeated Bayezid I at the Battle of Ankara in 1402 and took the city, but in 1403 Angora was again under Ottoman control.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Levant Company maintained a factory in the town from 1639 to 1768.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In the 19th century, its population was estimated at 20,000 to 60,000.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It was sacked by Egyptians under Ibrahim Pasha in 1832.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] From 1867 to 1922, the city served as the capital of the Angora Vilayet, which included most of ancient Galatia.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Prior to World War I, the town had a British consulate and a population of around 28,000, roughly 1⁄3 of whom were Christian.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In response, the leader of the Turkish nationalist movement, Mustafa Kemal Atatürk, established the headquarters of his resistance movement in Angora in 1920.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After the Turkish War of Independence was won and the Treaty of Sèvres was superseded by the Treaty of Lausanne (1923), the Turkish nationalists replaced the Ottoman Empire with the Republic of Turkey on 29 October 1923.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] A few days earlier, Angora had officially replaced Constantinople as the new Turkish capital city, on 13 October 1923, and Republican officials declared that the city's name is Ankara.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After Ankara became the capital of the newly founded Republic of Turkey, new development divided the city into an old section, called *Ulus*, and a new section, called *Yenişehir*.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ancient buildings reflecting Roman, Byzantine, and Ottoman history and narrow winding streets mark the old section.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The new section, now centered on Kızılay Square, has the trappings of a more modern city: wide streets, hotels, theaters, shopping malls, and high-rises.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Government offices and foreign embassies are also located in the new section.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara has experienced a phenomenal growth since it was made Turkey's capital in 1923, when it was "a small town of no importance".
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In 1924, the year after the government had moved there, Ankara had about 35,000 residents.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] By 1927 there were 44,553 residents and by 1950 the population had grown to 286,781.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After 1930, the city officially became known in Western languages as Ankara.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] By the late 1930s, the English name "Angora" was no longer in popular use.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara continued to grow rapidly during the latter half of the 20th century and eventually outranked İzmir as Turkey's second-largest city, after Istanbul.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara's urban population reached 4,587,558 in 2014, while the population of Ankara Province reached 5,150,072 in 2015.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Presidential Palace of Turkey is situated in Ankara.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] This building serves as the main residence of the president.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Geographically, Ankara is located in between the Kızılırmak and Sakarya rivers, and the Sakarya River forms its border with Eskişehir in the west.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara shares its borders with Bolu and Çankırı in the north; Konya in the south and Kırıkkale in the east.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara and its province are located in the Central Anatolia Region of Turkey.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Çubuk Brook flows through the city center of Ankara.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It is connected in the western suburbs of the city to the Ankara River, which is a tributary of the Sakarya River.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara has a cold semi-arid climate under the Köppen climate classification (*BSk*), while under the Trewartha climate classification, the city is classified as humid continental (*Dc*).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Due to its elevation and inland location, Ankara has cold and snowy winters, and hot and dry summers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Rainfall occurs mostly during the spring and autumn.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city lies in USDA Hardiness zone 7b, and its annual average precipitation is fairly low at 414 millimeters (16 in), nevertheless precipitation can be observed throughout the year.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Monthly mean temperatures range from 0.9 °C (33.6 °F) in January to 24.3 °C (75.7 °F) in July, with an annual mean of 12.6 °C (54.7 °F).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara's overall temperature regime is very similar to New York City.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara had a population of 75,000 in 1927.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] There were 74,632 male residents and 48,882 female residents in Ankara according to the 1935 census.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] As of 2022, the population of the Ankara Province was 5,782,285.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] When Ankara became the capital of the Republic of Turkey in 1923, it was designated as a planned city for 500,000 future inhabitants.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] During the 1920s, 1930s and 1940s, the city grew in a planned and orderly pace.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] However, from the 1950s onward, the city grew much faster than envisioned, because unemployment and poverty forced people to migrate from the countryside into the city to seek a better standard of living.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] As a result, many illegal houses called gecekondu were built around the city, causing the unplanned and uncontrolled urban landscape of Ankara, as not enough planned housing could be built fast enough.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Although precariously built, the vast majority of them have electricity, running water and modern household amenities.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Nevertheless, many of these gecekondus have been replaced by huge public housing projects in the form of tower blocks such as Elvankent, Eryaman and Güzelkent; and also as mass housing compounds for military and civil service accommodation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Although many gecekondus still remain, they too are gradually being replaced by mass housing compounds, as empty land plots in the city of Ankara for new construction projects are becoming impossible to find.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Çorum and Yozgat, which are located in Central Anatolia and whose population is decreasing, are the provinces with the highest net migration to Ankara.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] About one third of the Central Anatolia population of 15,608,868 people resides in Ankara.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The literacy rate in the whole province for people who are 15 years old or older is 98.18% according to 2020 TÜİK data.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara Province also has the highest percentage of tertiary education graduates in Turkey with 29.08% of the population having either an undergraduate, master's or doctor's degree.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara has long been a productive agricultural region in Anatolia.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In the Ottoman period, Ankara was well known for producing grain, cotton, and fruits.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city has exported mohair (from the Angora goat) and Angora wool (from the Angora rabbit) internationally for centuries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In the 19th century, the city also exported substantial amounts of goat and cat skins, gum, wax, honey, berries, and madder root.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It was connected to Istanbul by railway before the First World War, continuing to export mohair, wool, berries, and grain.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Central Anatolia Region is one of the primary locations of grape and wine production in Turkey, and Ankara is particularly famous for its Kalecik Karası and Muscat grapes; and its Kavaklıdere wine, which is produced in the Kavaklıdere neighborhood within the Çankaya district of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara is the center of the state-owned and private Turkish defence and aerospace companies, where the industrial plants and headquarters of the Turkish Aerospace Industries, MKE, ASELSAN, HAVELSAN, ROKETSAN, FNSS, Nurol Makina, and numerous other firms are located.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Exports to foreign countries from these defense and aerospace firms have steadily increased in the past decades.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The IDEF in Ankara is one of the largest international expositions of the global arms industry.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] A number of the global automotive companies also have production facilities in Ankara, such as the German bus and truck manufacturer MAN SE.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara hosts the OSTIM Industrial Zone, Turkey's largest industrial park.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] A large percentage of the complicated employment in Ankara is provided by the state institutions; such as the ministries, subministries, and other administrative bodies of the Turkish government.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] There are also many foreign citizens working as diplomats or clerks in the embassies of their respective countries.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The *Electricity, Gas, Bus General Directorate* (EGO) operates the Ankara Metro and other forms of public transportation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara is served by a suburban railway named Başkentray (B1), 1 light rail transit line named Ankaray (A1) and 2 Metro lines (M1-M2-M3, M4) of the Ankara Metro with about 400,000 total daily commuters, while additional lines (A2, M5, M6, M7, M8) are planned.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara Central Station is a major rail hub in Turkey.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Turkish State Railways operates passenger train service from Ankara to other major cities, such as: Istanbul, Eskişehir, Balıkesir, Kütahya, İzmir, Kayseri, Adana, Kars, Elazığ, Malatya, Diyarbakır, Karabük, Zonguldak and Sivas.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Commuter rail also runs between the stations of Sincan and Kayaş.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] On 13 March 2009, the new Yüksek Hızlı Tren (YHT) high-speed rail service began operation between Ankara and Eskişehir.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] On 23 August 2011, another YHT high-speed line commercially started its service between Ankara and Konya.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] On 25 July 2014, the Ankara–Istanbul high-speed line of YHT entered service.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara Esenboğa Airport, located in the north-east of the city, is Ankara's main airport.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Whilst the AŞTİ is the main coach terminal.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The average amount of time people spend commuting on public transit in Ankara on a weekday is 71 minutes.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] 17% of public transit passengers, ride for more than two hours every day.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The average amount of time people wait at a stop or station for public transit is sixteen minutes, while 28% of users wait for over twenty minutes on average every day.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The average distance people usually ride in a single trip with public transit is 9.9 km (6.2 mi), while 27% travel for over 12 km (7.5 mi) in a single direction.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Since 8 April 2019, the mayor of Ankara is Mansur Yavaş from the Republican People's Party (CHP), who won the mayoral election in 2019 and 2024.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ankara is politically a triple battleground between the ruling conservative AK Party, the opposition Kemalist center-left Republican People's Party (CHP) and the nationalist far-right MHP.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The province of Ankara is divided into 25 districts.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Historically, the CHP's key and almost only political stronghold in Ankara lay within the central area of Çankaya, which is the city's most populous district.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] While the CHP has always gained between 60 and 70% of the vote in Çankaya since 2002, political support elsewhere throughout Ankara was minimal.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Overall, the AK Party enjoyed the most support throughout the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The electorate of Ankara thus tended to vote in favor of the political right, far more so than the other main cities of Istanbul and İzmir.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In retrospect, the 2013–14 protests against the AK Party government were particularly strong in Ankara, proving to be fatal on multiple occasions.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city suffered from a series of terrorist attacks in 2015 and 2016, most notably on 10 October 2015; 17 February 2016; and 13 March 2016.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The city was also one of the sites of the coup attempt on 15 July 2016.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Melih Gökçek was the Metropolitan Mayor of Ankara between 1994 and 2017.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Initially elected in the 1994 local elections, he was re-elected in 1999, 2004 and 2009.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In the 2014 local elections, Gökçek stood for a fifth term.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The MHP's metropolitan mayoral candidate for the 2009 local elections, Mansur Yavaş, stood as the CHP's candidate against Gökçek in 2014.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] In a heavily controversial election, Gökçek was declared the winner by just 1% ahead of Yavaş amid allegations of systematic electoral fraud.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] With the Supreme Electoral Council and courts rejecting his appeals, Yavaş declared his intention to take the irregularities to the European Court of Human Rights.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Although Gökçek was inaugurated for a fifth term, most election observers believe that Yavaş was the winner of the election.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Gökçek resigned on 28 October 2017 and was replaced by the former mayor of Sincan district, Mustafa Tuna; who was succeeded by Mansur Yavaş of the CHP, the current mayor of Ankara, elected in 2019.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The foundations of the Ankara castle and citadel were laid by the Galatians on a prominent lava outcrop (39°56′28″N 32°51′50″E﻿ / ﻿39.941°N 32.864°E﻿ / 39.941; 32.864), and the rest was completed by the Romans.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Byzantines and Seljuks further made restorations and additions.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The area around and inside the citadel, being the oldest part of Ankara, contains many fine examples of traditional architecture.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] There are also recreational areas to relax.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Many restored traditional Turkish houses inside the citadel area have found new life as restaurants, serving local cuisine.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The citadel was depicted in various Turkish banknotes during 1927–1952 and 1983–1989.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The remains, the stage, and the backstage of the Antique Rome theatre of Ankara can be seen outside the castle.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Roman statues that were found here are exhibited in the Museum of Anatolian Civilizations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The seating area is still under excavation.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Augusteum, now known as the Temple of Augustus and Rome, was built 25 x 20 BC following the conquest of Central Anatolia by the Roman Empire.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ancyra then formed the capital of the new province of Galatia.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] After the death of Augustus in AD 14, a copy of the text of the *Res Gestae Divi Augusti* (the *Monumentum Ancyranum*) was inscribed on the interior of the temple's **pronaos** in Latin and a Greek translation on an exterior wall of the **cella**.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The temple on the ancient acropolis of Ancyra was enlarged in the 2nd century and converted into a church in the 5th century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It is located in the Ulus quarter of the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It was subsequently publicized by the Austrian ambassador Ogier Ghiselin de Busbecq in the 16th century.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Roman Baths of Ankara have all the typical features of a classical Roman bath complex: a *frigidarium* (cold room), a *tepidarium* (warm room) and a *caldarium* (hot room).
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The baths were built during the reign of the Roman emperor Caracalla in the early 3rd century to honor Asclepios, the God of Medicine.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Today, only the basement and first floors remain.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Roman Road of Ankara or *Cardo Maximus* was found in 1995 by Turkish archeologist Cevdet Bayburtluoğlu.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It is 216 meters (709 feet) long and 6.7 meters (22.0 feet) wide.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Many ancient artifacts were discovered during the excavations along the road and most of them are displayed at the Museum of Anatolian Civilizations.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The Column of Julian or Julianus, now in the Ulus district, was erected in honor of the Roman emperor Julian the Apostate's visit to Ancyra in 362.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Kocatepe Mosque is the largest mosque in the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Located in the Kocatepe quarter, it was constructed between 1967 and 1987 in classical Ottoman style with four minarets.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Its size and prominent location have made it a landmark for the city.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Ahmet Hamdi Akseki Mosque is located near the Presidency of Religious Affairs on the Eskişehir Road.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] Built in the Turkish neoclassical style, it is one of the largest new mosques in the city, completed and opened in 2013.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] It can accommodate 6 thousand people during general prayers, and up to 30 thousand people during funeral prayers.
[src:artistic-billiards-world-championship/ankara-p01] The mosque was decorated with Anatolian Seljuk style patterns.
